,"tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"We really should have Starlark as a configuration language everywhere because it\u0026rsquo;s very expressive and easy to read/understand. Instead we\u0026rsquo;re stuck with ever increasing piles of YAML and obscure configuration formats that nobody wants to deal with.\nhttps://openrun.dev/blog/starlark ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18393/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"That\u0026rsquo;s a deep dive through layers and layers of abstraction from Rust to LLVM intrinsics to instruction expansion at the processor level.\nIt\u0026rsquo;s fascinating stuff but as much as I like Rust, I still have no idea at what point I would ever need such a thing.\nhttps://questdb.com/blog/rust-fetch-max-compiler-journey ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18391/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Software can only be proven right within a set of assumptions. Something as simple as leftpad can be broken in any number of interesting ways.\nhttps://lukeplant.me.uk/blog/posts/breaking-provably-correct-leftpad ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18389/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Maths","RelPermalink":"/categories/maths/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Visual explanations of mathematical concepts are nice if they work. Here\u0026rsquo;s one such explanation of functional optics which is almost kinda accessible.\nhttps://marcosh.github.io/post/2025/10/07/the-mondrian-introduction-to-functional-optics.html ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18387/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Internet","RelPermalink":"/categories/internet/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"It\u0026rsquo;s always been my feeling that TLS has unacceptable collateral damage in how it breaks the web for normal people. That\u0026rsquo;s considered a bit of a crank opinion, but I\u0026rsquo;m definitely not the only person who feels that way.\nhttps://michael.orlitzky.com/articles/lets_not_encrypt.xhtml ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18385/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"The Bitter Lesson is an interesting concept. Stuffing the prompt runs into diminishing returns pretty quickly but on the other hand, getting your AI to play well with tools is challenging.\nhttps://blog.nilenso.com/blog/2025/10/14/bitter-lesson-applied-ai ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18383/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"}],"content":"Did anybody get any benefit from the fact that we are now stuck with Atom and RSS?\nThere\u0026rsquo;s a valuable lesson here about sucking it up and just accepting the popular thing.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18381/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Berlin","RelPermalink":"/categories/berlin/"},{"LinkTitle":"Deutsch","RelPermalink":"/categories/deutsch/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"}],"content":"Cycling home from having done groceries yesterday night, I wondered why there were police officers with machine guns standing on the sidewalk.\nTurns out this was why: https://www.berlin.de/polizei/polizeimeldungen/2025/pressemitteilung.1606865.php ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18379/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"The marketing that DHH does for projects was always bad, disingenuous and annoying.\nSo Rails users were OK with DHH back when he was pushing their shitty web framework of choice. But now all of a sudden they draw the line. He didnt change that much really.\nhttps://crimier.github.io/posts/Framework-Omarchy/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18378/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"It was obvious long ago that DHH is a problem for the Rails community. After recent events the situation seems to have finally become untenable.\nhttps://tekin.co.uk/2025/09/the-ruby-community-has-a-dhh-problem ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18372/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"An explanation of the AT Protocol and how it could be the open layer that allows everybody to own their data.\nhttps://overreacted.io/open-social ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18370/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Every programming language has to strike a balance when it comes to abstraction and none of them get it right. Rust is written in a way that is often too abstract for the things that you want to do with it.\nhttps://corrode.dev/blog/simple ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18368/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Github is over and many leading edge developers have already moved off or are seriously considering it.\nhttps://www.mistys-internet.website/blog/blog/2024/07/12/github-is-starting-to-feel-like-legacy-software ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18366/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"We should have more histories of software. There are lots of things that have been tried out and learned which if they aren\u0026rsquo;t captured will disappear entirely.\nhttps://mergify.com/blog/the-origin-story-of-merge-queues ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18364/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"The guide to sqlite query planning and tuning is cool, but what\u0026rsquo;s even better is that this kind of scale and optimisations are possible at all with sqlite.\nhttps://emschwartz.me/subtleties-of-sqlite-indexes ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18362/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"The situation described here where AI writes 90% of the code is almost entirely the same as how any software engineer works already. The only thing that\u0026rsquo;s changing is that instead of code you\u0026rsquo;re writing instructions to the LLM.\nhttps://lucumr.pocoo.org/2025/9/29/90-percent ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18360/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Philosophy","RelPermalink":"/categories/philosophy/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"},{"LinkTitle":"Reading","RelPermalink":"/categories/reading/"}],"content":" He is a Marxist who understands the importance of money and markets; without Marx, you cannot understand the movement of history, but without money, you cant do anything about it.\nFirst of all, times are changing, and we have to change with them, and if we dont well die, which is completely normal.\nThere are companies and organizations that are very interested in ideas and culture and are very willing to support projects related to these themes.\nElites no longer know what guidance to provide, and debate constantly among themselves over what aspects of our civilization to embrace, meaning that we lack values and a clear sense of direction.\nWhen secularism overwhelms civil society, peoples mentalities always change and morality declines.\nBut once such a value system is established, I think Chinese civilization will become universal, at which point, people will no longer identify with American values, and instead Chinese values that will become a truth acknowledged everywhere.\nThus what we propose is to \u0026ldquo;face the future, rely on tradition, engage the present.\u0026rdquo;In other words, we should be guided by the future even as we keep our basis in tradition and continue our search in daily practice.\nWe cannot, in the name of pursuing socialism, disallow the market economy, because pure socialism is inefficient.So we need the market economy to be in the mix, and the core elements of the market economy are private capital, which means the long-term existence of private ownership.But on the other hand, it would not be right to merely emphasize the efficiency of the private economy and cast aside state-owned enterprises. State-owned enterprises play many roles that are irreplaceable; they form the basis of the national economy and are important in strategic development, high-end technological research, and the relatively even distribution of social wealth.So both are indispensable.\nA truly constructive and effective media atmosphere is built on a premise, which is that all actors possess a high degree of civic engagement.This is not only a right but a responsibility, meaning that you cannot only criticize others , but have to be adept at self-criticism as well.This is what a mature citizen of a modern country should be.However, a large number of people active in online media do not possess the abilities that healthy citizens should have. They actively fight for rights and freedom of speech but have little awareness of the responsibilities that these rights imply. What we see on the Internet is very much like a cultural atmosphere formed on the basis of a small-scale peasant economy.They focus on one thing to the exclusion of everything else, they band together with people who think like they do and denounce everyone else, inciting extreme emotions.The media ecology in such an atmosphere is truly very bad.\nThe most critical thing for the media is not the degree of freedom of speech, but whether the media can grasp the main line of historical progress, at a moment when history is at a turning point and nothing is very clear, and then follow that line and direction and its internal laws and demands to run your newspaper, write the articles, and have your say. Generally speaking, the chance of making mistakes will be smaller this way.\nIn an era of rapid industrialization, as wealth increases, people\u0026rsquo;s awareness of their rights and the importance of contracts also increases.So in times like these, people will be thinking more in terms of liberalism, so how can we not reflect this in what we publish?But for similar reasons, as wealth increases, so does inequality, moral corruption, and environmental harm.So socialist demands for equality and for attention to the environment bubble up, and how can we not reflect demands for socialism in our work\nBut sooner or later, questions concerning the longer term or the essence of something will surface, at which point the best of these younger generations, the true elites, will feel the pain that comes with these questions, and they will wake up from their immersion in instant gratification and look for answers to the problems.\nThere are fewer and fewer intellectuals who can relate to reality, and they have been replaced by more and more academics who write for smaller and smaller audiences.\nIf contemporary intellectuals cannot grasp todays practice of social production and todays technological revolution, then they will be eliminated sooner or later. In my opinion, 95% of intellectuals are already gone.\nhttps://www.readingthechinadream.com/yang-ping-on-beijing-cultural-review.html ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18085/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"}],"content":" This week economists have been congratulating themselves on following Acemoglu, Johnson and Robinson into institutions. They are, in effect,proud to have discovered the rest of the social sciences.\nAcemoglu and Robinson read a book calledAmerican Slavery, American Freedom, used the bits about American freedom and tossed the bits about American slavery.\nIf youre going to study institutions, you have to be curious about all of them.\nThis year the Riksbank awarded its prize to a treatment of early modern institutions so selective it functions as a bedtime story for capitalists. The good institutions produced prosperity. The bad ones produced misery.\nhttps://www.ft.com/content/1e2584d6-65ef-46de-bfb2-28811be65600 ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/17638/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Podcast","RelPermalink":"/categories/podcast/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"}],"content":"Listening to this episode on the trial of John Brown I gasped several times. It\u0026rsquo;s a wild story of deep moral conviction and powerful oratory.\nhttps://pocketcasts.com/podcast/past-present-future/05615c70-bc1a-013b-f3f7-0acc26574db2/politics-on-trial-john-brown-vs-slavery/a1278a0f-072b-42de-8c12-e33f7267bf10?t=2409.0 ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18354/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Glad to see improvements like this can be made without fuss and drama. The ASF is obviously better and long overdue.\nhttps://www.phoronix.com/news/New-Apache-Software-Logo ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18352/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Internet","RelPermalink":"/categories/internet/"},{"LinkTitle":"Kids","RelPermalink":"/categories/kids/"},{"LinkTitle":"San-Francisco","RelPermalink":"/categories/san-francisco/"}],"content":"At some point you have to ask yourself how many predators work at Meta. They seem hell bent on targeting children. You don\u0026rsquo;t have to be a predator to work at Meta but it helps.\nRemind me again what happens to a pizzeria that is suspected of doing something like this.\nhttps://www.theguardian.com/technology/2025/sep/20/parents-outraged-meta-uses-photos-schoolgirls-ads-man ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18349/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Climate","RelPermalink":"/categories/climate/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"}],"content":" The point is that once again China is teaching us to think at scale. The future scale of a more developed, post-Western world is gigantic. If we are to have any hope of climate stabilization the only realistic policy, therefore, is not some twee Western European vision of sustainability, it is radical and transformative. Cities will be bigger, energy needs will be bigger, production will be bigger than anything we have previously conceived.\nclean energy needs not just to be efficient, or optimal, it needs to bebludgeoningly, overwhelmingly, unanswerably DOMINANT .\nThis cycle is precisely what we need. China is teaching the world to think big.\nRight now, Beijing is offering cheap, clean power, employment, trade and a route to prosperity. Washington is offering tariffs, policy chaos, White nationalist memes and South Korean workers in shackles after a raid on an EV battery factory. This is no way to win the grand strategic contest of the 21st century.\nhttps://adamtooze.substack.com/p/chartbook-409-beyond-the-marshall ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18348/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Gleam is truly a dream of a programming language. I\u0026rsquo;m looking forward to launch my project and do more with it.\nhttps://mtlynch.io/notes/gleam-first-impressions ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18346/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Compared to the way I had to learn about B-trees (poorly photocopied sheets bound into a reader), this interactive page is a dream.\nhttps://planetscale.com/blog/btrees-and-database-indexes ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18344/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Postgres is *the* database engine (together with sqlite) and knowledge about its internals is becoming more than a nice to have.\nhttps://drew.silcock.dev/blog/how-postgres-stores-data-on-disk ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18342/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Litestar is an interesting addition to the list of Python microframeworks with a lot going for it.\nhttps://www.b-list.org/weblog/2025/aug/06/litestar ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18340/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"We\u0026rsquo;re seeing increasingly more posts about jj coming out and I can\u0026rsquo;t repeat enough that it is totally worth switching away from git.\nhttps://maddie.wtf/posts/2025-07-21-jujutsu-for-busy-devs ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18337/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Every time I have to cross-compile something (usually in Rust to run on the cloud somewhere) it\u0026rsquo;s always rather confusing to figure out the correct target triples. Weird that something that\u0026rsquo;s this fundamental is documented this poorly.\nhttps://mcyoung.xyz/2025/04/14/target-triples ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18335/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Agile","RelPermalink":"/categories/agile/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"}],"content":"That\u0026rsquo;s definitely a phrase worth remembering:\nSlow is smooth, smooth isfast.\nChasing \u0026ldquo;more\u0026rdquo; and \u0026ldquo;faster\u0026rdquo; is often not much more than a distraction from the things you should be doing.\nhttps://raitner.de/en/2022/09/slow-is-smooth-smooth-isfast/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18332/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"The write-up how Bun can be so fast is a good exploration in all the things that computers are good at now. Machines and our networks have gotten much faster and much more parallel which influences what an optimal approach to building software is now.\nWe don\u0026rsquo;t use Bun but I\u0026rsquo;m happy to see that even on these benchmarks pnpm is no slouch. You could do much worse than that.\nhttps://bun.com/blog/behind-the-scenes-of-bun-install ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18328/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Berlin","RelPermalink":"/categories/berlin/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Internet","RelPermalink":"/categories/internet/"},{"LinkTitle":"New-York","RelPermalink":"/categories/new-york/"}],"content":"Subway Takes is publishing episodes they filmed in Berlins U-Bahn, and the results are both amusing and unexpectedly revealing.\nThe show itself needs almost no introduction since its become a mainstream online phenomenon. Subway Takes features comedian and musician Kareem talking to NYC personalities who share their takes during brief subway rides.\nHe ventures outside of New York once in a while, and after London and Paris, has now turned up in Berlin.\nThe U-takes started with a masked party-goer declaring that Its actually good for you to party for 72 hours. Next came local comedian Aurel Mertz with a pedestrian and mildly funny take about exercise. The party-goer made a return appearance after the aforementioned 72 hours of partying. And the latest episode features an American investor affecting an exaggerated German accent.\nThese three characters could not be a better reflection of the city of Berlin and where its at. A guy stuck in a party, unable to get out; a Southern German guy slumming it here until its not fun anymore; and an investor mining the city for cash and clout. These are the people who shape the city, and for all of them, this place is a playground.\nWhat I take away from these Subway Takes is that Berlin is a place where nothing matters and everybody is passing through. Could they have even found a real Berliner to talk to? Thats a question thats probably best not even asked.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/u-bahn-takes/","tags":[],"title":"U-Bahn Takes"},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Product-/-Design","RelPermalink":"/categories/product-/-design/"}],"content":"The disabled creating custom prosthetics and turning themselves into highly visible and fashionable neo-people is at least one positive way that cyberpunk is turning into reality.\nhttps://www.chinadailyhk.com/hk/article/618682 ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18320/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Work","RelPermalink":"/categories/work/"}],"content":"Attitudes towards part-time employment of men are a good proxy indicator of how sophisticated the economy is and also of gender equality.\nFrom my own experience Germany and the Netherlands are markedly different on this front and the statistics prove it with a 2x difference in part-time men.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18319/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"An excellent Jujutsu reference covering most of the basic operations you will need.\nhttps://justinpombrio.net/src/jj-cheat-sheet.pdf ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18316/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"The AWS CEO doing not much more than stating the obvious when it comes to AI and software engineering.\nhttps://www.theregister.com/2025/08/21/aws_ceo_entry_level_jobs_opinion ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18314/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Internet","RelPermalink":"/categories/internet/"},{"LinkTitle":"Kids","RelPermalink":"/categories/kids/"}],"content":"Meta\u0026rsquo;s push towards sexualised chatbots for children is very concerning and nobody should let their kids use any of Zuckerberg\u0026rsquo;s platforms unsupervised.\nhttps://www.cbc.ca/music/neil-young-quit-facebook-instagram-chatbots-1.7611518 ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18312/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Internet","RelPermalink":"/categories/internet/"},{"LinkTitle":"Product-/-Design","RelPermalink":"/categories/product-/-design/"}],"content":"Not the first time Meta created racy bots and it will probably not be the last unless Taylor Swift sues them. I guess they do need to get more talent in to create things that are actually useful.\nhttps://www.reuters.com/business/meta-created-flirty-chatbots-taylor-swift-other-celebrities-without-permission-2025-08-29 ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18307/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Berlin","RelPermalink":"/categories/berlin/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Games","RelPermalink":"/categories/games/"},{"LinkTitle":"Product-/-Design","RelPermalink":"/categories/product-/-design/"},{"LinkTitle":"San-Francisco","RelPermalink":"/categories/san-francisco/"}],"content":"How much time for an innovative/edgy/creative agency to copy this (poorly) in Berlin?\nhttps://www.wired.com/story/pursuit-scavenger-hunt-san-francisco ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18305/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Climate","RelPermalink":"/categories/climate/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"}],"content":"Paris has published a climate adaptation plan for a 50C future. In Berlin I guess we\u0026rsquo;ll just ignore it as long as possible.\nhttps://www.ekopolis.fr/ressources/rapport-paris-50degc-mission-dinformation-et-devaluation-du-conseil-de-paris ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18303/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"A good description of how if software engineering was setup for speed of iteration we would have entirely different environments than we have now. Nobody is really opposed to speed, but nobody really wants it either so we end up with bloated development and bloated results that are the worst of all compromises.\nhttps://inessential.com/2025/08/28/easy-app-writing.html ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18301/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Product-/-Design","RelPermalink":"/categories/product-/-design/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Congratulations to That Browser Company on what must be a stellar exit for them.\nNo idea what Atlassian can do with this because it is the place where technology goes to die.\nhttps://www.cnbc.com/2025/09/04/atlassian-the-browser-company-deal.html ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18299/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Cycling","RelPermalink":"/categories/cycling/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"London","RelPermalink":"/categories/london/"}],"content":"Cycling in London is more joyful than in Berlin and I feel its more of a cycling city now.\nBut in either place, as this video argues, youd be crazy not to take a bike to get around.\nhttps://youtu.be/Dmf6aEx09Oo?si=xI6QIxxaekoxG280 ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18297/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"New-York","RelPermalink":"/categories/new-york/"},{"LinkTitle":"Product-/-Design","RelPermalink":"/categories/product-/-design/"},{"LinkTitle":"San-Francisco","RelPermalink":"/categories/san-francisco/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"This may sound harsh, but its a lot fairer than they deserve: But since the product is no longer jumping exponentially in capabilities, they will need to fall back on proper product development if they want to be competitive. They need to accept that they are softwareplain old softwareand that means people need to be able to use it.\nhttps://aboard.com/desperately-seeking-software/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18296/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"}],"content":"This is the kind of deep and rational thinking we should expect to see from the billionaires who own most of the world. Jeff Bezos, one of the richest people in the world, got so demonised that he had to have a cry about it.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18291/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Maths","RelPermalink":"/categories/maths/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"A very cool and simple introduction into Lean and what makes it interesting. I\u0026rsquo;m not sure exactly what draws people in this direction but it\u0026rsquo;s cool to see the progress that\u0026rsquo;s being made here.\nhttps://overreacted.io/the-math-is-haunted ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18289/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Internet","RelPermalink":"/categories/internet/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Perplexity lost its momentum almost a year ago and everything they\u0026rsquo;ve been doing since has been stuff like this. It takes some effort to stand out as a bad actor in a field like this, but here they are.\nhttps://blog.cloudflare.com/perplexity-is-using-stealth-undeclared-crawlers-to-evade-website-no-crawl-directives ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18287/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"I had a very similar mediocre experience using LLMs with Python/Rust/Typescript where I didn\u0026rsquo;t really see the point. Only when I started using Go for a recent hackathon project did I get the fully hands off experience where I didn\u0026rsquo;t have to write any code.\nI\u0026rsquo;ve long been on the record saying that type systems are bad and I think this is a big part of what makes Rust/Typescript difficult to track for the LLM.\nThe problem with Python I think is more that it is too permissive and anything can be anything (and whatever typing we put on top is rather weak and non-standard). I was particularly surprised to notice how much easier it is to readwhen working with an LLM I pretty much only read codeGo code than Python code for much of the same reasons.\nhttps://lucumr.pocoo.org/2025/8/4/shitty-types ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18285/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Claude Code is the best in class code assistant out there right now, so it\u0026rsquo;s interesting to see how it works under the hood and how it has evolved.\nThe differences in experience using these tools are so big, that you can\u0026rsquo;t really consider any of them as being in the same class as Claude Code.\nhttps://mariozechner.at/posts/2025-08-03-cchistory ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18283/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Maths","RelPermalink":"/categories/maths/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Solvers are very annoying to setup and plug your problem into if you\u0026rsquo;re using them regularly. That\u0026rsquo;s why hooking them into LLMs to do the annoying manipulation work is an amazing idea.\nThis has the potential to entirely evaporate a vast class of quite complex problems.\nhttps://www.stephendiehl.com/posts/smt_and_mcp_solvers ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18281/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Now that I\u0026rsquo;ve switched entirely to jj, I never have to think about git\u0026rsquo;s confusing terminology or absurd design ever again.\nAnd there sure is a lot of bad things to go around, here\u0026rsquo;s one list drafted by Julia Evans.\nhttps://jvns.ca/blog/2023/11/01/confusing-git-terminology ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18279/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"The Javascript Date class is so criminally bad, that you will have a better score if you give random answers than if you try to reason about it.\nhttps://jsdate.wtf ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18277/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"}],"content":"Imagine a foreign language being pervasive in your country for no real reason whatsoever. The Uzbeks are right in wanting to rip it out.\nhttps://thediplomat.com/2025/06/russian-without-russians-the-politics-of-language-in-uzbekistan/?utm_source=substack\u0026amp;utm_medium=email ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18275/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Video","RelPermalink":"/categories/video/"}],"content":"Glad to see I\u0026rsquo;m not the only person hooked by these short videos. They\u0026rsquo;re oddly compelling and are at the moment still mostly under the radar here.\nhttps://www.wired.com/story/china-reel-short-dramas-video-social-media ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18273/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"I\u0026rsquo;ve found it very useful to use jj to continuously and automatically snapshot the changes that Claude makes. This way if it does anything that I didn\u0026rsquo;t want, it\u0026rsquo;s incredibly easy to undo it and still keep a clean history.\nHere\u0026rsquo;s what my hackathon project looks like in the gg client after several days of on and off development.\nYou can have Claude do these steps as well. It\u0026rsquo;s pretty good at jj describe even if a bit verbose. And in most cases it could also do jj new before every change, something that I forget occasionally.\nI didn\u0026rsquo;t bother with that because it will mess up the exact ordering of commands and then I\u0026rsquo;ll be busy sorting out which edits should go into which change. Having the change viewer side by side with the Claude Code terminal gives me the most control and oversight.\nThis way my flow is:\njj new Ask Claude Code to do something Check the output in gg Have Claude Code iterate Have Claude Code do the jj describe Either jj new or jj abandon depending on whether I think the result is going somewhere I think at this point I kinda forgot how I would do this in git and I\u0026rsquo;m also not particularly interested in learning it anymore either.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/keeping-claude-in-check-with-jujutsu/","tags":[],"title":"Keeping Claude in check with Jujutsu"},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"At scale you will be slapped in the face by this tail or that all the time. It\u0026rsquo;s a clear and simple argument to rehabilitate the mean as the measurement we should be looking at.\nhttps://brooker.co.za/blog/2021/04/19/latency.html ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18268/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Leadership","RelPermalink":"/categories/leadership/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Complaining about the Cloud has become fashionable and it\u0026rsquo;s an easy thing to do. What\u0026rsquo;s not so easy is to create strategic room to maneuver.\nI enjoyed these pieces by Will Kelly in part also because they are very glib. They connect because they contain a kernel of truth. The real way to get out of the cloud is indeed: Real ops maturity. Procurement leverage. The discipline to say no to vendor convenience. That\u0026rsquo;s the real work for anybody who\u0026rsquo;s interested in doing it.\nhttps://willkelly.substack.com/p/the-cloud-repatriation-story-is-a ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18264/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"One of the best ways to learn anything (including Git) is to make the entire thing yourself from scratch. Obsess over the details.\nhttps://drew.silcock.dev/blog/artisanal-git ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18262/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Science","RelPermalink":"/categories/science/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"For the many people who may not be intimately familiar with the workings of Turing machines, this visual and interactive guide should get them up to speed really nicely.\nIt\u0026rsquo;s mostly just the mechanics of the machine and doesn\u0026rsquo;t go into the more fun and formal parts such as reductions and proofs. But it\u0026rsquo;s a start.\nhttps://samwho.dev/turing-machines ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18256/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"},{"LinkTitle":"Video","RelPermalink":"/categories/video/"}],"content":"A very informative write-up of how you would squeeze out the last bits of performance out of a Rust port. Not sure if I\u0026rsquo;d ever apply this but I\u0026rsquo;m happy enough that I can mostly follow along.\nhttps://ohadravid.github.io/posts/2025-05-rav1d-faster ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18254/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Product-/-Design","RelPermalink":"/categories/product-/-design/"}],"content":"It doesn\u0026rsquo;t really matter that much what is next for iOS. We should agree that flat design was a mistake.\nhttps://www.lux.camera/physicality-the-new-age-of-ui ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18251/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"To hearken back to the previous comparison of Java versus compiled languages, AWS has a case here where a naive rewrite of their JVM database in Rust created massive performance wins.\nAt this point, you need to be asking yourself: Why would anybody ever write a database in Java?\nhttps://www.allthingsdistributed.com/2025/05/just-make-it-scale-an-aurora-dsql-story.html ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18248/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Cycling","RelPermalink":"/categories/cycling/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Product-/-Design","RelPermalink":"/categories/product-/-design/"}],"content":"\u0026ldquo;Nightmare bicycle\u0026rdquo; is a concept that I won\u0026rsquo;t get out of my head quickly.\nhttps://www.geoffreylitt.com/2025/03/03/the-nightmare-bicycle.html ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18245/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"},{"LinkTitle":"Work","RelPermalink":"/categories/work/"}],"content":"It\u0026rsquo;s relevant to my interests to read how others have massively scaled the systems we use. Discord has a solid write-up here of how to deal with Elastic Search.\nWhich is all good and well, but I\u0026rsquo;m a bit sad that we have so much systems software written in Java which in some cases works well (Kafka, Spring) but in other cases is a bit of a slog (Elastic, Cassandra). There are Rust/C++ search stores out there which out of the box beat a Java solution 2-5x on speed and 1/10th on memory usage. Those are numbers that make a huge difference at scale.\nhttps://discord.com/blog/how-discord-indexes-trillions-of-messages ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18243/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Agile","RelPermalink":"/categories/agile/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Science","RelPermalink":"/categories/science/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"A twofer on software estimation that also tallies with my intuition. People are really great at estimating the median which is impossible to communicate to people without deep intuition for software engineering and statistics.\nIt makes total sense as a guideline to multiply your initial guess x1.6 for the mean, x5 for the 95th percentile and x10 for the 99th percentile. This is also why deadlines are irrelevant and counterproductive in software engineering. There are much better ways to achieve the same goals.\nhttps://thesearesystems.substack.com/p/task-estimation-conquering-hofstadters https://erikbern.com/2019/04/15/why-software-projects-take-longer-than-you-think-a-statistical-model.html ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18238/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"I fully agree with Paolo Scanferla here that very complex typing (\u0026ldquo;hyper-typing\u0026rdquo;) is an impediment to get anything done but besides the technical aspects, here are some ratchets here that are very pernicious.\nCreating very complex typing is hard to argue against (\u0026ldquo;But don\u0026rsquo;t you see how this is safer?\u0026rdquo;) and simplicity rarely wins in group programming environments. You\u0026rsquo;re essentially arguing against somebody who\u0026rsquo;s posturing as being very clever (\u0026ldquo;It\u0026rsquo;s very easy and safe this way.\u0026rdquo;). Once you lose the initial argument and the complexity gets in, it\u0026rsquo;s impossible to get out again. It will only expand in your code base and make everything it touches also overly complex. Getting this out is several orders of magnitude more work than getting it in and can only be done by (the very few) people who understand the entire thing. Those people have made an excellent manoeuvre for their own job security and against everybody else\u0026rsquo;s productivity. This kind of typing is not incidental. The very design of Typescript and its increasingly more and more complex type system is meant to enable this. Language features that are there will always be used and regularly misused. It\u0026rsquo;s near impossible to guard against that. That\u0026rsquo;s why I consider any language with an overly expressive type system to be suspect (and this is why Go is good). Liking Typescript is a code smell on the person. https://pscanf.com/s/341 ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18235/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Using the same Github account for work that you also use to do anything and everything else with is not particularly secure. That\u0026rsquo;s why I split my presence on the platform, but getting everything to work that way has been somewhat annoying.\nI found this guide by Rahul Pandey that\u0026rsquo;s been a huge help in how to take a lot of the pain out of it.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18233/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Leadership","RelPermalink":"/categories/leadership/"},{"LinkTitle":"Science","RelPermalink":"/categories/science/"}],"content":"The Return To Office debate has been very contentious and hardly productive. Here in HBR is an ethics based approach to create solutions here that work for everybody. A lot of it is common sense but this is coherent and a useful lens.\nhttps://hbr.org/2025/05/the-workplace-psychological-contract-is-broken-heres-how-to-fix-it ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18231/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Science","RelPermalink":"/categories/science/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"We use reservoir sampling a lot day to day and here\u0026rsquo;s a great visual explanation of how this algorithm does this seemingly impossible task.\nhttps://samwho.dev/reservoir-sampling ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18229/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Thorsten Ball keeps writing bangers such as this speed run how to write a AI coding agent.\nIt always feels to me that Cursor is mostly a balancing act of hacking a collaborative editor into the VSCode codebase (poorly) more than it is chockfull of LLM based innovations.\nhttps://ampcode.com/how-to-build-an-agent ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18223/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Science","RelPermalink":"/categories/science/"}],"content":"A dive into Stafford Beer\u0026rsquo;s systems thinking that uncovers the ANT-style depth that\u0026rsquo;s often glossed over. That notwithstanding, I still think the glib and reductive POSIWID has its uses.\nhttps://joelitobarski.com/posiwid/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18220/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Leadership","RelPermalink":"/categories/leadership/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Solid and sober career advice in the current landscape.\nhttps://lethain.com/career-advice-2025 ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18216/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Agile","RelPermalink":"/categories/agile/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"I could quote this entire article by Dan North :\nIt takes daily resolve and good habits. It takes effort and deliberate practice to train yourself to unsee the general case; to not reach for a library first because it is only adding a single dependency; to not prematurely abstract or DRY code because reasons; to not over-invest in a component because we have blanket coding standards with arbitrary rules like percentage of test coverage; to go back and stabilise that component you sketched to see if it would work, and it did; to excise that component you sketched that did not work out.\nBuilding software this way is the perfect balance of freedom and discipline. As the author mentions it\u0026rsquo;s a matter of taste and experience and extremely hard to learn in any other way than by doing it.\nBSSN ( Best and Simple and Now) is the answer to \u0026ldquo;you should not build garbage\u0026rdquo; and \u0026ldquo;you should not overcomplicate your code prematurely\u0026rdquo; either.\nSketching in particular is a quality that should also apply to code (and will be impossible to explain to anybody who does not already get it).\nSketching does not mean hacking! I know many more engineers who are good at proper code than those who can sketch well. Sketching is about providingjust enoughquality that you can sustain a direction, knowing you can go back and fill in the blanks later on (or throw away the sketch with minimal investment lost). Hacked code quickly becomes unmanageable. Well-sketched code is just a lighter-weight version of the real thing.\nhttps://dannorth.net/best-simple-system-for-now ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18213/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Something that I also need to try. The rise of overlay networks that can create private networks and make all your devices and servers internet addressable is a huge convenience.\nhttps://blog.6nok.org/tailscale-is-pretty-useful/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18209/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Here\u0026rsquo;s a topic over at Lobsters of what a bunch of software engineers would like to see programmed out in the world. Every ask gets a bunch of suggestions of things out there that could fill that gap.\nThree hundred plus replies in this is a deep view of how much still remains unexplored in the software engineering problem and solution space.\nhttps://lobste.rs/s/btjtkr/what_software_do_you_dream_about_do_not ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18206/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Leadership","RelPermalink":"/categories/leadership/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":" Should managers beinthe code? Yes, absolutely. Should managerswritecode? Maybe, but it also depends on what you mean by writing code.\nA good answer to the age old question. I ship more code right now than I ever have.\nhttps://theengineeringmanager.substack.com/p/should-managers-still-code ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18204/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"A thought provoking attack on SQL with a bunch of pointers and hints as to what could come next. I\u0026rsquo;m pretty competent with SQL but that is exactly the point where you should become interested in what the limitations are and in what situations it makes sense to break out of the paradigm.\nhttps://www.scattered-thoughts.net/writing/against-sql ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18202/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"I\u0026rsquo;m not a huge fan of these \u0026ldquo;best programmer\u0026rdquo; lists, but this list was better than most that I have seen.\nhttps://endler.dev/2025/best-programmers ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18200/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"The amount of positive things happening around Python packaging and performance is really cool to see. Here\u0026rsquo;s a way to compile Python directly to Webassembly and get much better performance.\nhttps://lukasz.langa.pl/f37aa97a-9ea3-4aeb-b6a0-9daeea5a7505 ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18198/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"I\u0026rsquo;ve never used a tool that supports interdiff code reviews, but seeing it described here, it makes intuitive sense and I would love to have this. Instead we are\u0026ndash;as is pretty much everybody else\u0026ndash;stuck on Github.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18195/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Leadership","RelPermalink":"/categories/leadership/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":" All of those things listen above are insupportof your primary goal: ensuring that you are getting shit done. You cannot get shit done to a world-class level by leaving all of the details to other people.\nA great argument for being in the details as a manager and a lot of examples of what that can mean for your org and situation.\nhttps://www.theengineeringmanager.com/managing-managers/being-in-the-details/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18193/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Leadership","RelPermalink":"/categories/leadership/"},{"LinkTitle":"Strategy","RelPermalink":"/categories/strategy/"}],"content":"I guess NVIDIA got lucky and ARM also got lucky and AMD also got lucky. Everybody got lucky except for Intel.\nhttps://www.tomshardware.com/tech-industry/artificial-intelligence/at-nvidias-gtc-event-pat-gelsinger-reiterated-that-jensen-got-lucky-with-ai-intel-missed-the-boat-with-larrabee ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18185/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Berlin","RelPermalink":"/categories/berlin/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Leadership","RelPermalink":"/categories/leadership/"}],"content":"We have kids in two parallel classes at school which lets us compare things directly and gives us insights many of the other parents don\u0026rsquo;t have.\nOne class was doing great and the other one was struggling, this also made the parents of that class become frustrated and non-constructive. I\u0026rsquo;m in two Whatsapp groups and can compare the vibe and noise level of both directly.\nThen the class that was struggling got a clinch new staff member and the class that was doing well\u0026rsquo;s teachers got disbanded and the atmosphere among the parents changed night and day. Now the parents who were chill are creating way more noise and the other parents are much more constructive and relaxed.\nI\u0026rsquo;ll take this as a leadership lesson: No Bad Teams, Only Bad Leaders\nhttps://www.actioncoach.co.za/no-bad-teams-only-bad-leaders/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18183/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Last time I talked about how I use jj for small code changes while being interrupted all the time as a manager . This time we\u0026rsquo;ll be using it in anger.\nOpen Sourcing a Project I\u0026rsquo;ve been long overdue to open source my little side project Cuppings . This is always annoying because pretty much every project will have a bunch of sensitive stuff checked in at some point. In this case the repository contains a Google Maps API key (as well as the entire database, but that\u0026rsquo;s a different story) which is something I definitely do not want to share with the internet ((Github may have an integration with Google for this so the API key may be disabled as soon as the repo is public anyway, but who knows.)).\nThe core problem is that cloud costs cannot be effectively limited on any platform. This seems to be a deliberate profit maximising move from the platforms more than because of any technical limitation. Standard operating procedure here is to rotate the key and call it a day. I wanted to be a bit more thorough than that.\nWhat I\u0026rsquo;m doing is this:\nDelete the API key from the account. Detach my personal credit card from the Google Cloud project. - It turns out that this is impossible. Scrub the secret out of the repo and its entire history. Get rid of any branches that may still have the secret. - Pretty easy because I don\u0026rsquo;t use branches on my own projects. The account management steps are easy and boring. Let\u0026rsquo;s get to the secret scrubbing.\nScrubbing the Secret Classically you would do this with git-filter-branch and that\u0026rsquo;s always a bit annoying because it only works on entire files. Here, the secret had spread through the project and I wanted to leave the other bits of code intact. It looked like jj should be suited for the job.\nI started off reading the docs and trying to piece together a sequence of actions that could work.\nFalse Starts There were some false starts and I couldn\u0026rsquo;t get out of them so I threw the repo checkout away and started again. For all the praise that the jj op log gets I have so far never been able to use it to get myself out of a mess.\nOne thing that may be helpful in the future is to use jj op abandon instead of jj op undo. Undo adds another operation to the oplog which I find confusing. Often you just want to entirely get rid of the last things that you did.\nAnother issue that I had was that any editor watching the folder would run a language server and if anywhere during our trip through history the correct .gitignore wasn\u0026rsquo;t in place, jj would start snapshotting all the build files while in the middle of this very delicate operation.\nI got around that by disabling the language server entirely like here with a setting for Helix .\nFinding the Right Starting Point What really made a difference here is jj\u0026rsquo;s revset syntax with its functions for both filenames and changed text:\njj log -r \u0026#39;files(\u0026#34;backend/.env\u0026#34;)\u0026#39; -p jj log -r \u0026#39;diff_contains(\u0026#34;GOOGLE_API_KEY=\u0026#34;)\u0026#39; The -p shows the entire patch instead of a short view which is particularly handy to see which change to the .env file added the secret.\nThen to have an overview of where I am, I\u0026rsquo;ll have gg open on the side. For git I can\u0026rsquo;t do any serious work without gitup and it\u0026rsquo;s very much the same with jj. The terminal outputhowever good it isdoes not give me the same amount of tangible feeling that a GUI does.\nIt is possible to manipulate the repository using gg and when it works it\u0026rsquo;s pretty nifty but I\u0026rsquo;ve found that mixing operations between the GUI and the command-line is not super reliable and can make gg crash out. That\u0026rsquo;s why I use gg purely as a viewer and I make all the changes from the command-line.\nRewriting History I seem to have missed one occurrence on my last pass because when searching right now I find another occurrence.\nLooking at the diff with jj show rkq shows me there\u0026rsquo;s still an unredacted API key there.\nSo we might as well clear this as well.\nTrying to change this with jj edit rkq throws an error because the change is immutable. Anything that has a descendent in immutable_heads() is immutable. This is a safety setting to make sure you don\u0026rsquo;t accidentally rewrite shared history.\nOur history is not shared because this is my private side project, so we can do whatever we want. With jj edit rkq --ignore-immutable it is possible to edit this history as well. I replace the API key with the word \u0026ldquo;fake\u0026rdquo;.\nThat works and propagates the change through history but it also creates conflicts.\nFixing Conflicts My view in gg looks like this now:\nThe command-line looks similar if you know what to look for (the red crosses).\nHow I go through this is to scroll down in gg to find the first occurrence of the conflict. The change has propagated to that point where it conflicted again and needs to be fixed. That\u0026rsquo;s here.\nFrom there I edit the first conflicted change with jj edit qtv to fix it. The edit command helpfully immediately prints out which files are conflicted at this point.\nIt\u0026rsquo;s the .env file again and it looks like this.\nThis is pretty quick to fix with Helix. Delete all the lines which shouldn\u0026rsquo;t be there, pick the ones you want to have and remove all conflict markers.\nWe don\u0026rsquo;t have to add anything after fixing the conflict or do something like git rebase --continue because jj picks the new state up automatically, sees the conflict is gone and propagates that up.\nThis clears up a bunch of the commits and we scroll up to find the next one. After doing that a couple of times the entire history is conflict free.\nPush it back Now the only thing left is to check we didn\u0026rsquo;t destroy anything and to push the bookmark back to the forge with jj bookmark move main --to @ and jj git push -b main.\nYou can garbage collect things before if you want to make sure the changes are no longer there jj util gc.\nAfter completing this operation I seem to have lost the position of some WIP branches I had on the old tree, but as this is a side project I can live with that. I\u0026rsquo;m curious if it would have been possible to keep these.\nFeedback I wrote this in part from memory after having done other things for a few weeks so I may have gotten some points wrong but all in all this should roughly work. Any suggestions or additions are welcome.\nUpdate: One addition is that this will remove the change from git history but the strings will likely still be in the op log and evolog. Whether they are truly gone from any git housekeeping files is also not completely verified.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/scrubbing-secrets-with-jj/","tags":[],"title":"Scrubbing Secrets with jj"},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Deutsch","RelPermalink":"/categories/deutsch/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"}],"content":"An idea this dumb could only come from one of two people in Germany (Httges or Thelen). DOGE\u0026rsquo;s main aim is to burn down the entire government.\nHttges leads a company which is only upright because it abuses its monopoly position. There has never been any value creation there.\nhttps://www.tagesschau.de/wirtschaft/unternehmen/telekom-chef-doge-100.html ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18176/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Running a public website these days means staving off attacks from every LLM company in the world trying to get your data (legally or illegally).\nhttps://status.sr.ht/issues/2025-03-17-git.sr.ht-llms ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18174/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Leadership","RelPermalink":"/categories/leadership/"},{"LinkTitle":"Reading","RelPermalink":"/categories/reading/"},{"LinkTitle":"San-Francisco","RelPermalink":"/categories/san-francisco/"}],"content":"Wasn\u0026rsquo;t it the CEO of META going around telling everybody that free speech was the most important thing at the moment?\nhttps://www.reuters.com/legal/meta-wins-halt-promotion-careless-people-tell-all-book-by-former-employee-2025-03-13 ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18172/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"},{"LinkTitle":"Video","RelPermalink":"/categories/video/"}],"content":"Type level programming in Typescript has been driven to the point of pure absurdity by implementing a DOOM runtime on it to play the game with.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18170/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Climate","RelPermalink":"/categories/climate/"},{"LinkTitle":"Deutsch","RelPermalink":"/categories/deutsch/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"}],"content":"A weird coincidence how a media campaign would lead to double digit billions in extra revenues for fossil fuel providers (and to worse outcomes for everybody wanting to heat their homes in Germany). Nothing behind this probably.\nhttps://www.pv-magazine.de/2025/02/26/die-verdeckten-kosten-der-heizhammer-kampagne-24-milliarden-euro-mehrumsatz-fuer-die-gaserzeuger/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18168/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Sports","RelPermalink":"/categories/sports/"}],"content":" When you have a more well-rounded life, it doesnt take away, it doesnt distract you as an athlete, Courtney told him. It makes you stronger and better. And able to have a clear head when you get the opportunity to line upI bring who I am to the bike. But the bike does not make me who I am.\nNotes on elite performance that support why being well rounded and having interests outside of your core pursuit is a good thing.\nhttps://davidepstein.substack.com/p/why-hobbies-are-an-advantage-not ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18166/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"We liked to pretend that it was possible to use American cloud providers with any measure of sovereignty, but that pretence is going to drop very soon now. Not sure what the alternatives are, but everybody should be planning for some drastic changes here.\nhttps://berthub.eu/articles/posts/you-can-no-longer-base-your-government-and-society-on-us-clouds ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18164/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Product-/-Design","RelPermalink":"/categories/product-/-design/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"A good overview of how Git developers configure git for themselves with a bunch of settings that should be the default for everybody but which will take ages to be rolled out. You should copy most of these into your own config.\nhttps://blog.gitbutler.com/how-git-core-devs-configure-git ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18162/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"I think this critique of Flamework is a bit rich coming from the author of Flask with its global request object. But there is a point in being able to iterate really quickly, it\u0026rsquo;s even better to be able to work crudely without creating a disastrous unmaintainable mess.\nThere is a difference between writing terrible code well or writing beautiful code poorly.\nhttps://lucumr.pocoo.org/2025/2/20/ugly-code ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18157/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"}],"content":"\u0026ldquo;The only good laws are the laws that make *me* more money.\u0026rdquo;\nhttps://techcrunch.com/2025/03/13/y-combinator-urges-the-white-house-to-support-europes-digital-markets-act/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18145/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Games","RelPermalink":"/categories/games/"},{"LinkTitle":"Product-/-Design","RelPermalink":"/categories/product-/-design/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Chronicle of how you make a hit game. Balatro is amazing even if I ripped through it in a couple of days.\nhttps://localthunk.com/blog/balatro-timeline-3aarh ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18141/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Podcast","RelPermalink":"/categories/podcast/"},{"LinkTitle":"Product-/-Design","RelPermalink":"/categories/product-/-design/"}],"content":"I usually enjoy Cortex\u0026rsquo;s romps into productivity porn, but what struck me here is that they open with Grey discovering Asana and how he spent the week setting his business and life up in it.\nLots to unpack here:\nPeople are still discovering Asana?\nGrey immediately and deeply gets what is powerful about Asana and what tradeoffs that entails.\nI think that everybody who refuses to use Asana is forced to cobble together a broken version of it themselves. That is true and will stay true.\nhttps://www.relay.fm/cortex/164 ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18137/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Our work in software engineering consists mostly of learning and for me and my team a fair part of that is teaching. Both of these are immensely difficult and rewarding components of the job.\nhttps://www.herostrat.us/posts/learning-the-hardest-problem-in-computer-science ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18135/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Leadership","RelPermalink":"/categories/leadership/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Here\u0026rsquo;s a good article about platform teams that I got to read an early draft of. I can say from my own experience that all of these traps are very easy to go into. Be aware and prioritize ruthlessly what works and what doesn\u0026rsquo;t work.\nhttps://serce.me/posts/2025-01-07-six-sins-of-platform-teams ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18131/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"I think when people ask what\u0026rsquo;s so great about jj they tend to go deep into things such as mega-merge strategies and stacked PRs . These things are cool, no doubt, but jj can be useful starting from the very small.\nIn my case as a manager I commit a lot of small stuff, documentation updates, nits, fixes (and also larger bits of code). I got this down to be pretty fast using all the git aliases available.\nIn an ideal world I\u0026rsquo;d be doing most of my work in a worktree (which takes ages to create in our monorepo) and I could pass the change quickly in my clean main checkout folder. That would then go like this:\ngcb random-new-branch ga docs.md gcm \u0026#34;Documentation update\u0026#34; # Or immediately gcam gpu But of course as a manager, my life is made out of interruptions so odds are that my main checkout folder is not clean and contains changes for something else I started but did not get to finish. Now I have a bunch of bad options:\nQuickly finish the old work and push it so I can work on the new thing Create a worktree for this tiny thing Stash the old work and risk forgetting about it entirely Think all of the above is too much effort and I\u0026rsquo;d just rather drop this Go to Github.com and pass the change through the web site (best option if I can do it in one go) With jj I don\u0026rsquo;t have to deal with most of this. Whenever I have something new I want to work on I can type: jj new main and I\u0026rsquo;m good to go. Whatever work in progress I might\u0026rsquo;ve had, has already been snapshotted and will still be there when I want to resume work on it.\nAnd when it\u0026rsquo;s ready, I can do jj git push -c and it will send my change to our forge without me having to name the branch. I still have to describe the change but all in all jj has turned 4 steps into 2 and removed the potential blockers from this process.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/using-jj-as-a-manager/","tags":[],"title":"Using jj as a manager"},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"New-York","RelPermalink":"/categories/new-york/"},{"LinkTitle":"Photography","RelPermalink":"/categories/photography/"},{"LinkTitle":"Product-/-Design","RelPermalink":"/categories/product-/-design/"}],"content":"A beautiful lush essay and homage to an ubiquitous typeface without a name.\nhttps://aresluna.org/the-hardest-working-font-in-manhattan ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18124/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"I can relate to this because I\u0026rsquo;m using Cursor to write a bit of Gleam where it\u0026rsquo;s usually off entirely because this is such a small language.\nIt would be annoying maybe if LLMs got us into a place where literally everything becomes a React+Tailwind application but so far I don\u0026rsquo;t see a huge risk that that will happen.\nWhat is available and what is easy does of course influence what becomes popular, but nothing new there.\nhttps://vale.rocks/posts/ai-is-stifling-tech-adoption ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18122/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Climate","RelPermalink":"/categories/climate/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"}],"content":"So much car traffic is absolutely unnecessary which makes it all the more galling that we allow people to poison everybody else by doing it.\nhttps://www.theguardian.com/environment/2025/feb/14/brake-pad-dust-toxic-exhaust-emissions ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18120/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Internet","RelPermalink":"/categories/internet/"},{"LinkTitle":"Science","RelPermalink":"/categories/science/"}],"content":"Lots of people are going to have a problem with the truth going forward, so get those Wikipedia backups handy and start thinking about how to host it in a more distributed and resilient way.\nhttps://www.404media.co/wikipedia-prepares-for-increase-in-threats-to-us-editors-from-musk-and-his-allies ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18117/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"},{"LinkTitle":"San-Francisco","RelPermalink":"/categories/san-francisco/"}],"content":"Not a major surprise that minorities would be treated poorly at a nazi charity like the Chan Zuckerberg Initiative.\nhttps://www.businessinsider.com/chan-zuckerberg-initiative-racial-discrimination-claim-ray-holgado-facebook-2020-11?international=true\u0026amp;r=US\u0026amp;IR=T ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18107/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Video","RelPermalink":"/categories/video/"}],"content":"Wheel of Time is low key one of the best fantasy tv shows out right now. Each season is going from strength to strength and the next one looks to be the best one yet.\nhttps://youtu.be/qk0D4OV95bQ?si=q02qV8EUy1XA-ivH ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18105/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"A lot has been made of this talk about Egoless Engineering but I can say that for me it came at the exactly right time. In our platform team we got to the point mentioned in the talk and are now working on #3: Empower Everybody Else.\nhttps://egoless.engineering/#50 ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18102/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Obsidian is a knowledge worker\u0026rsquo;s lightsaber. It\u0026rsquo;s indispensable for any kind of serious work and it is now free to use.\nhttps://obsidian.md/blog/free-for-work ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18099/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Rare to see an actual apples-to-apples comparison of databases like this. Postgres comes out ahead versus Sqlite but as always, it depends.\nhttps://www.twilio.com/en-us/blog/sqlite-postgresql-complicated ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18096/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Another funny relic from the depths of version control: the Octopus Merge\nhttps://www.freblogg.com/git-octopus-merge ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18093/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"This is the way A Pattern Language intended we should talk about patterns: applied and without making things more complicated. Patterns should simplify and be grasped immediately.\nhttps://grantslatton.com/design-patterns ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18090/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Filing this away for future reference when at some point we\u0026rsquo;ll want to get out of managed Kubernetes.\nhttps://bilbof.com/posts/kubernetes-on-hetzner ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18087/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"A very good explanation about \u0026ldquo;object soup\u0026rdquo; and how Rust is uniquely poorly suited to model problems in that way. It pins down a very fundamental issue that people coming from an object oriented background run into all the time and offers a helpful solution.\nhttps://jacko.io/object_soup.html ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18081/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Science","RelPermalink":"/categories/science/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Quanta\u0026rsquo;s write-ups of math discoveries are always enjoyable to read. In this case an undergraduate (!) figured out something new about hash tables and how fast they can be. Not sure yet when this will be shipped in code, but still it\u0026rsquo;s a pretty amazing discovery.\nhttps://www.quantamagazine.org/undergraduate-upends-a-40-year-old-data-science-conjecture-20250210/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/18077/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Turkish","RelPermalink":"/categories/turkish/"}],"content":"An enjoyable dive into where all these