le/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"The manifesto to choose boring technology in order to be able to solve interesting problems is something to (re-)read regularly until you\u0026rsquo;ve internalized it.\nhttp://boringtechnology.club/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15594/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Work","RelPermalink":"/categories/work/"}],"content":"A nice rundown of Good Strategy/Bad Strategy as recounted by Russell Davies to Anna Schipman.\nhttps://www.annashipman.co.uk/jfdi/russells-strategy-advice.html ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15592/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Agile","RelPermalink":"/categories/agile/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Internet","RelPermalink":"/categories/internet/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"Cloudflare is setting a high bar for post-mortem writing but if you want to get started with this, the only parts you really need are: What went wrong \u0026amp; What are we doing about it.\nhttps://blog.cloudflare.com/details-of-the-cloudflare-outage-on-july-2-2019/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15590/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"The-City","RelPermalink":"/categories/the-city/"}],"content":"OV-Fiets is the bike share avant-la-lettre, but it\u0026rsquo;s so locally Dutch that it always has been a bit hard to explain. The popularity of OV-Fiets has increased, now coinciding nicely with the international boom in mobility.\nhttps://bicycledutch.wordpress.com/2019/07/24/no-limits-to-the-success-of-the-public-transport-bicycle/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15588/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Nederlands","RelPermalink":"/categories/nederlands/"},{"LinkTitle":"Reading","RelPermalink":"/categories/reading/"}],"content":" Opvallend is dat ze vaak een groot gevoel voor uiterlijke schoonheid hebben.\nIntens: enthousiast, uitbundig, gepassioneerd, diepzinnig, levendig, hartstochtelijk, innig, fanatiek\n(in plaats van hysterisch, overdreven, driftig, wild, luidruchtig, ongeremd)\nGevoelig: inlevend, empathisch, openstaand, zachtaardig, teder, toegankelijk\n(in plaats van sentimenteel, kwetsbaar, prikkelbaar, overgevoelig, slap)\nOpmerkzaam: oog voor detail, scherpzinnig, oplettend, alert, aandachtig, waakzaam, kritisch, geconcentreerd, oplettend\n(in plaats van pietluttig, lastig, kieskeurig, snel afgeleid)\nSterke wil: vastberaden, doelgericht, eigenzinnig, onverstoorbaar, krachtig, aanhoudend, standvastig\n(in plaats van koppig, halsstarrig, onhandelbaar, opstandig, dwars, hardnekkig, eigenwijs)\nOok als je je kind op school ophaalt bijvoorbeeld, helpt het als je even op ooghoogte van je kind komt en zegt: H lieverd, fijn dat je er bent.\nLaat je kind vaak weten dat je blij bent dat hij er is. Wat bof ik toch dat ik jouw mama mag zijn of Wat gezellig om samen met jou een boekje te lezen laten je kind voelen dat hij er mag zijn zonder dat hij daar iets speciaals voor hoeft te doen.\nHoe beter jij door hebt waar hij last van heeft, hoe beter je het voor hem kunt benoemen. Dat was schrikken, h? of Vind je die koffie vies ruiken of is het dat gekookte ei op mijn boterham?\nPuur en alleen al het idee dat ze moeten doen wat een ander bepaalt kan zorgen voor heel veel verzet, zelfs als datgene wat ze moeten doen in feite helemaal niet zo erg is.\nDe gebiedende wijs doet het vaak erg slecht bij kinderen met een erg sterke wil.\nZe wil dus echt wel rekening houden met wat ik nodig heb, maar ik moet daar dan wel duidelijk over zijn.\nHoud gezinsvergaderingen\nPlan vergaderingen in om met elkaar te bespreken hoe het allemaal loopt. Is iedereen nog tevreden over de gemaakte afspraken, zijn er nieuwe nodig, lukt het iedereen om zich eraan te houden?\nZolang de afspraak geldt, moet iedereen zich eraan houden. Dus ook als je kind er eens geen zin in heeft, zal hij zich aan zijn deel van de afspraak moeten houden. Als je het er gewoon bij laat zitten omdat je geen zin hebt in gezeur, kom je natuurlijk nergens. Afspraak is afspraak. Zeg dit ook tegen je kind.\nZo leer je hem dat hij zelf ergens voor verantwoordelijk blijft en dat hij, ook al kan hij niet waarmaken wat hij heeft toegezegd, het er dan niet zomaar bij kan laten zitten. Vertel hem dat er helemaal niets mis mee is om in gezamenlijk overleg af te wijken van afspraken, maar dat het heel lastig is als iemand zonder enig overleg zijn deel van de afspraak niet nakomt.\nMisschien denk je nu wel dat dit allemaal heel tijdrovend is. Deels is dit ook zo. Je moet echt de tijd nemen om met je kind in gesprek te gaan. Toch duren deze gesprekjes in de praktijk vaak maar een paar minuutjes. Deze tijd win je vaak direct daarna al weer terug omdat hij geen weerstand meer heeft tegen wat er moet gebeuren.\nAls het dus al lukt om je kind zich goed te laten gedragen door middel van straffen (en die kans is klein bij temperamentvolle kinderen), dan komt dat doordat je zijn wil gebroken hebt. Dat is erg zonde. Je wilt je kind graag in zijn kracht zetten en niet die kracht juist om zeep helpen.\nVrijwel alle ouders geven aan dat, juist als ze hun kind de ruimte geven om zich echt te ontladen, de intensiteit van die ontlading op den duur ontzettend afneemt.\nZet jezelf en je eigen overtuigingen even aan de kant. Hij doet dit niet om jou dwars te zitten of omdat hij niet wt hoe hij zich moet gedragen, hij kn het nu gewoon niet. En als iemand iets niet kan, heeft hij hulp nodig, geen preek.\nOok wanneer je kind steeds bewust gedrag vertoont waarvan hij heel goed weet dat jij daar last van hebt of wanneer hij de hele tijd zonder duidelijke aanleiding zijn broertje of zusje loopt te treiteren, kan dit betekenen dat hij zich moet ontladen.\nSommige ouders voelen zich aan het einde van de dag vooral rot over wat er allemaal niet goed ging. Als je dat doet, doe je jezelf daarmee enorm tekort.\nBedenk dat je kind minstens n iemand nodig heeft die onvoorwaardelijk achter hem staat, hem altijd volledig accepteert en steeds het beste in hem ziet. Iemand die in hem blijft geloven als hij er een potje van maakt en hem steeds een nieuwe kans geeft.\nBoos worden op een temperamentvol kind werkt ontzettend averechts. Hij raakt er alleen maar meer overprikkeld van, waardoor de situatie nog verder escaleert. Wat hij nodig heeft, is een liefdevolle ouder die op een natuurlijke manier leiding neemt als dat nodig is, die zijn eigen grenzen op een rustige manier aangeeft en die een baken van rust is op het moment dat zijn kind volledig overmand wordt door emoties.\nStress ontstaat ook doordat je ergens bent, terwijl je eigenlijk ergens anders wilt zijn.\nLaat hem eventueel wat water drinken. Hierdoor gaan zijn darmen namelijk werken en daardoor wordt zijn lichaam ook wakkerder.\nIk word gek van de rotzooi is voor de meeste kinderen namelijk geen legitieme reden.\nAlle frustraties, overprikkeling of emoties die hij onder schooltijd even parkeert, gooit hij jou thuis juist voor je voeten. Hoe irritant dat misschien ook is, het is eigenlijk een goed teken. Bij jou voelt hij zich zo veilig dat hij alles eruit durft te gooien.\nVraag hem in dat laatste geval wat er precies besproken moet worden en wat hij graag zou willen veranderen. Op die manier kun je er wel voor hem zijn en hem helpen, maar neem je het toch niet allemaal uit handen.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/highlights-for-temperamentvolle-kinderen/","tags":[],"title":"Highlights for Temperamentvolle Kinderen"},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Agile","RelPermalink":"/categories/agile/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"London","RelPermalink":"/categories/london/"}],"content":"For the more abstract work, it makes it a lot easier for other people to read your mind and for you to delegate if you share as much context as possible as Anna Shipman describes here.\nhttps://www.annashipman.co.uk/jfdi/delegating-to-a-team.html ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15582/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Agile","RelPermalink":"/categories/agile/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"}],"content":"Something that bears pointing out regularly: Plus, contrary to popular belief, agile practices were not invented by the Agile movement. They predate it by many decades.\nhttps://medium.com/columbus-egg/dear-agile-im-tired-of-pretending-d39ab6a12003 ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15580/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Berlin","RelPermalink":"/categories/berlin/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"London","RelPermalink":"/categories/london/"},{"LinkTitle":"Work","RelPermalink":"/categories/work/"}],"content":"Cath writes some very salient points about growing into leadership that on the one hand should be more widespread, but on the other hand, everybody will likely have to find out for themselves.\nAlso nice to see this local group of people taking the next steps in their careers if even only witnessed from afar like this.\nhttps://medium.com/@ohrworm/what-ive-learnt-about-leadership-3ff83b06a1de ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15577/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Work","RelPermalink":"/categories/work/"}],"content":"A very recognizable story of an engineering organization finding itself and one person\u0026rsquo;s journey into leadership and back.\nThe step to leadership should definitely not be a one-way door. People can\u0026rsquo;t really know beforehand that they want to do this and even if they rollback, everybody will be much better off for having tried it.\nhttps://medium.com/@FlippEng/from-engineer-to-manager-and-back-again-64e796d45945 ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15575/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Berlin","RelPermalink":"/categories/berlin/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"}],"content":"My foray into local politics showed me that more than anything the Grne are a party of yuppies without much or any social face behind it.\nhttps://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/jun/24/german-greens-rise-nation-divided ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15572/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"}],"content":"I haven\u0026rsquo;t read this profile of the Sacklers. I\u0026rsquo;ll only read one when it is profiling them because they will be executed for their crimes.\nhttps://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/06/david-sackler-pleads-his-case-on-the-opioid-epidemic ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15570/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Agile","RelPermalink":"/categories/agile/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"}],"content":"I\u0026rsquo;ve never exactly followed any framework but instead, I played it by ear and mixed and matched what worked best from wherever I could find it. That\u0026rsquo;s always a bit bothersome (but easily solved) when people want to work with the exact definition of something.\nFormalizing that approach as SWARMing (Scaling Without A Religious Methodology) is an interesting twist indeed.\nhttps://dannorth.net/2018/01/26/in-praise-of-swarming/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15568/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Deutsch","RelPermalink":"/categories/deutsch/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Kids","RelPermalink":"/categories/kids/"}],"content":"Whenever our kids are dismayed by somebody else, they come to us and say that there was either a human (ein Mensch!) or a kid (ein Kind!). No genders, no nothing.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15566/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"The-City","RelPermalink":"/categories/the-city/"}],"content":"Leaving this here because I\u0026rsquo;m going to need it more often:\nThe smart in smart city is not smart as in intelligent, it is smart as in upscale.\nhttps://www.citylab.com/design/2019/06/smart-city-photos-technology-marketing-branding-jibberjabber/592123/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15563/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"},{"LinkTitle":"Work","RelPermalink":"/categories/work/"}],"content":"Any programming language once it gets big enough will face pressure to turn into Java. PHP succumbed to it, let\u0026rsquo;s see where Go goes. Try isn\u0026rsquo;t that big of an issue but it is a path that eventually may lead to generics and other stuff.\nhttps://www.ardanlabs.com/blog/2019/07/an-open-letter-to-the-go-team-about-try.html ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15561/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"}],"content":"Not to put too fine a point on it, but the media will go to any lengths to ignore Bernie.\nhttps://www.politico.com/story/2019/07/03/harris-warren-2020-dems-poll-1396656 ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15559/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Internet","RelPermalink":"/categories/internet/"}],"content":"Too aggravating to even read this entire thing. I\u0026rsquo;ll have to get it together soon to delete my facebook account. Though I\u0026rsquo;ll still be locked into Instagram and Whatsapp then, so I think it would be best indeed if those services would be broken up.\nhttps://www.theverge.com/2019/6/19/18681845/facebook-moderator-interviews-video-trauma-ptsd-cognizant-tampa ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15551/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"},{"LinkTitle":"Video","RelPermalink":"/categories/video/"}],"content":"Ende Gelnde is the radical environmentalist movement against climate change and here they are blocking a strip mine.\nhttps://twitter.com/Ende __Gelaende/status/1142462960587223042\nProtesting is a core German competence. There is deep institutional knowledge of how and why to do this. At the drop of a hat and with a lot of organizing infrastructure, it is possible to get thousands of people to join something like this.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15549/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"}],"content":"AOC is correct. America is running concentration camps filled with kids.\nIf you\u0026rsquo;re American or working in America by the way, I think you\u0026rsquo;re somewhat complicit in this.\nhttps://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/21/us/migrant-children-border-soap.html ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15546/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Internet","RelPermalink":"/categories/internet/"},{"LinkTitle":"Reading","RelPermalink":"/categories/reading/"}],"content":"Are people paying the Medium article ransom?\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15544/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"}],"content":"Exceedingly rare to find a talk about programming that draws on both Christopher Alexander and James C. Scott, two authors that I keep coming back to myself.\nEven better that it uses them to explain why the Design Patterns failed, something that I also felt but couldn\u0026rsquo;t really put my finger onI always thought this is just a silly thing that Java people doand how they could be better.\nhttps://vimeo.com/248214009 https://www.deconstructconf.com/2017/brian-marick-patterns-failed-why-should-we-care ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/patterns-failed/","tags":[],"title":"Patterns failed"},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"},{"LinkTitle":"The-City","RelPermalink":"/categories/the-city/"}],"content":"Leaving this here for when the UBER thing finally comes crashing down.\nIt will probably be similar to AirBnB and any sharing startup that first destroys and remakes a large part of the world for the worse and then goes out of business.\nhttps://americanaffairsjournal.org/2019/05/ubers-path-of-destruction/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15540/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Agile","RelPermalink":"/categories/agile/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"This Jez Humble talk about Continuous Delivery is one of my all-time favorites. As a bonus at the end he also totally demolishes the Google Guy.\nhttps://vimeo.com/229954108 ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/jez-humble-continuous-delivery-in-agile/","tags":[],"title":"Jez Humble - Continuous Delivery in Agile"},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Berlin","RelPermalink":"/categories/berlin/"},{"LinkTitle":"Deutsch","RelPermalink":"/categories/deutsch/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Kids","RelPermalink":"/categories/kids/"}],"content":"Just like almost every public service in Berlin the pediatrician situation is absolute squalor. It\u0026rsquo;s impossible to find one who picks up the phone or takes on new patients ((Don\u0026rsquo;t bother tipping me a pediatrician unless you\u0026rsquo;re sure they take new patients.)).\nWe\u0026rsquo;ve had some bad incidents in the past with sketchy doctors because of this and now I\u0026rsquo;m trying to figure out why this is the way it is.\nCall my lead for a pediatrician\nWe\u0026rsquo;re very sorry but we can\u0026rsquo;t take any new patients. Call the Kassenrztliche Verein It\u0026rsquo;s not us who do this.\nI am told to call the Dachverband der Krankenkassen Call the Spitzenverband We do not determine how many pediatricians can settle in a given area.\nThe telephone person says they are a temp and do not have any channel up to their leadership. I\u0026rsquo;m told to call my own Krankenkasse. Call Techniker Kankenkasse Wir sind nicht dafr zustndig.\nThe person says they have the same problem on a personal level in Hamburg but can\u0026rsquo;t really do anything for me professionally. I am told to call the Kassenrztliche Verein Call KV (again)\nReception says that I can get a peds appointment sometime in the future from a different number of theirs (not what I want). I called this number before and they will not give me a pediatrician and that is if they bother to pick up the telephone. Every instance says Dafr sind wir nicht zustndig.and sends me on until I\u0026rsquo;ve closed the loop.\nIt\u0026rsquo;s not the first time that this happens. I\u0026rsquo;ve previously spent half an hour being sent in a loop between Polizei and Ordnungsamt. This is the way that Germany functions: nobody is responsible for anything and everybody in between can get fucked.\nCorollary: if it is impossible to figure out why something is the way it is, it is also impossible to fix it.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/finding-a-pediatrician-in-berlin/","tags":[],"title":"Figuring out why there is a shortage of pediatricians"},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"},{"LinkTitle":"Work","RelPermalink":"/categories/work/"}],"content":"Lovely to see the Twisted community take the lead in moving Python forward and I fully support this idea of giving the standard library the Konmari treatment.\nhttps://glyph.twistedmatrix.com/2019/06/kernel-python.html ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15526/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Food","RelPermalink":"/categories/food/"}],"content":"There is another dirty secret behind the German switch to alcohol-free beers: German beers just aren\u0026rsquo;t that good. I prefer any major foreign beer (Heineken, Carlsberg, 1664, etc.) over most beers you can buy here.\nhttps://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jun/14/germans-thirsty-for-alcohol-free-beer-as-brewers-boost-taste ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15524/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Amsterdam","RelPermalink":"/categories/amsterdam/"},{"LinkTitle":"Berlin","RelPermalink":"/categories/berlin/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"}],"content":"Reading about Amsterdam canceling 10'000 parking spaces, does make me feel as if I\u0026rsquo;m living in an idiot\u0026rsquo;s city.\nhttps://www.citylab.com/transportation/2019/06/amsterdam-parking-spots-removal-cars-bikes-parks-playground/591067/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15522/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Internet","RelPermalink":"/categories/internet/"},{"LinkTitle":"Reading","RelPermalink":"/categories/reading/"}],"content":"I\u0026rsquo;ve stopped using Instapaper for a long time now, but I\u0026rsquo;m still reading longreads. Let me explain how.\nI go through my links in Chrome on my desktop. I close and read whatever I can and anything that\u0026rsquo;s too long stays in an open tab and floats slowly to the left.\nOn Chrome on my phone whenever I\u0026rsquo;m in transit or when I want to read something longer that isn\u0026rsquo;t a book, I go to the Recent tabsscreen. Besides those you can also find synced open tabs from all your other Chrome browsers. I then pick something that I want to read.\nNow, ideally it would allow me to close the tab on my desktop from my phone but understandably that\u0026rsquo;s not a feature. So I read a couple of articles, remember those and close the tabs manually next time I\u0026rsquo;m back on my desktop.\nThis works surprisingly well. Except for LRB articles. I have no clue what to do about those.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/a-poor-mans-instapaper/","tags":[],"title":"A poor man's instapaper"},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Reading","RelPermalink":"/categories/reading/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"},{"LinkTitle":"Work","RelPermalink":"/categories/work/"}],"content":" Amazon RedShift is a hosted version of ParAccel. More recently, a plethora of open source SQL-on-Hadoop projects have emerged; they are young but aiming to compete with commercial data warehouse systems. These include Apache Hive, Spark SQL, Cloudera Impala, Facebook Presto, Apache Tajo, and Apache Drill [52, 53].\nIn these situations, as long as people agree on what the format is, it often doesnt matter how pretty or efficient the format is. The difficulty of getting different organizations to agree on anything outweighs most other concerns.\nTherefore, to maintain backward compatibility, every field you add after the initial deployment of the schema must be optional or have a default value.\nThat means you can only remove a field that is optional (a required field can never be removed), and you can never use the same tag number again (because you may still have data written somewhere that includes the old tag number, and that field must be ignored by new code).\nIf you are using a system with multi-leader replication, it is worth being aware of these issues, carefully reading the documentation, and thoroughly testing your database to ensure that it really does provide the guarantees you believe it to have.\nToday, most data systems are not able to automatically compensate for such a highly skewed workload, so its the responsibility of the application to reduce the skew.\nUnfortunately, these tools dont directly translate to distributed systems, because a distributed system has no shared memoryonly messages sent over an unreliable network.\nSafety is often informally defined as nothing bad happens, and liveness as something good eventually happens.\nA much better solution is to build a brand-new database inside the batch job and write it as files to the jobs output directory in the distributed filesystem, just like the search indexes in the last section. Those data files are then immutable once written, and can be loaded in bulk into servers that handle read-only queries. Various key-value stores support building database files in MapReduce jobs, including Voldemort [46], Terrapin [47], ElephantDB [48], and HBase bulk loading [49].\nA complex system that works is invariably found to have evolved from a simple system that works. The inverse proposition also appears to be true: A complex system designed from scratch never works and cannot be made to work.\nJohn Gall, Systemantics (1975)\nWhen copies of the same data need to be maintained in several storage systems in order to satisfy different access patterns, you need to be very clear about the inputs and outputs: where is data written first, and which representations are derived from which sources? How do you get data into all the right places, in the right formats?\nIt would be very natural to extend this programming model to also allow a server to push state-change events into this client-side event pipeline. Thus, state changes could flow through an end-to-end write path: from the interaction on one device that triggers a state change, via event logs and through several derived data systems and stream processors, all the way to the user interface of a person observing the state on another device.\nBut this choice is not free either: if a service is so popular that it is regarded by most people as essential for basic social participation[99], then it is not reasonable to expect people to opt out of this serviceusing it is de facto mandatory.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/highlights-for-designing-data-intensive-applications/","tags":[],"title":"Highlights for Designing Data-Intensive Applications"},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"},{"LinkTitle":"Work","RelPermalink":"/categories/work/"}],"content":"A frankly amazing piece by Monica Lent using her experience to debunk seven commonly held truths about programming with verve. Programming consists of folklore and beliefs are often just beliefs. That indeed makes most learning in this field a question of unlearning.\nhttps://monicalent.com/blog/2019/06/03/absolute-truths-unlearned-as-junior-developer/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15512/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Work","RelPermalink":"/categories/work/"}],"content":"A case for becoming good at writing for software engineers that frankly holds up for anybody in a growing organization.\nhttps://blog.pragmaticengineer.com/on-writing-well/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15510/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"},{"LinkTitle":"The-City","RelPermalink":"/categories/the-city/"},{"LinkTitle":"Travel","RelPermalink":"/categories/travel/"}],"content":" As the blisters develop and his feet start to bleed, Walton asks the right questions. What are the human and environmental costs of Singapores success, and are they sustainable?\nHis conclusions are more nuanced than either Singapores detractors or its cheerleaders would like. The islands vaunted meritocracy is imperfect, especially seen from the perspective of its Malay and Indian minorities; and the pressures on citizens to perform and conform are so intense that those who do not fit in sometimes opt for voluntary exile.\nNot having walked the length of the island (which sounds amazing) but talking about Singapore from afar, I came to many of the same conclusions. Still a fascinating place in so so many ways.\nhttps://www.ft.com/content/fbbb28d2-885c-11e9-97ea-05ac2431f453 ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15508/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"},{"LinkTitle":"Work","RelPermalink":"/categories/work/"}],"content":"A nicely put explanation for why I too pick my environments to be maximally productive with minimal configuration. In many cases, I just make do to the disgust of those who\u0026rsquo;ve learned all the shortcuts and applied all the customizations, but to them I\u0026rsquo;d say: marginal returns and opportunity cost.\nhttp://sstephenson.us/posts/on-configuration ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15504/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"},{"LinkTitle":"Work","RelPermalink":"/categories/work/"}],"content":"I\u0026rsquo;d dare say that with the waning of the iPhone as a platform (both for development and for business), Apple\u0026rsquo;s closed plays will be increasingly lackluster. I\u0026rsquo;ve been rooting for Swift but it\u0026rsquo;s a horse running in the wrong race.\nhttps://onezero.medium.com/to-revive-the-mac-apple-wants-to-kill-electron-154873336e78 ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15502/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"The-City","RelPermalink":"/categories/the-city/"}],"content":" Its no coincidence that co-living start-ups have gravitated to cities like Berlin, San Francisco, London and New York. Ostensibly winning the battle for capital and talent, they are urban testing-grounds, where rootless and cashed-up tech workers, heated real estate markets, and rising housing pressures add up to a recipe for experimentation.\nAn interesting look at co-living but please let\u0026rsquo;s not change the entire city into this nonsense.\nhttps://assemblepapers.com.au/2019/05/20/redesigning-renting-housing-as-a-service/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15499/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Internet","RelPermalink":"/categories/internet/"},{"LinkTitle":"Product-/-Design","RelPermalink":"/categories/product-/-design/"}],"content":"About password managers:\nBut I never found a way to get people onto 1password in a single training session. The setup process has a lot of moving parts, involving the desktop app, browser plugin, online service, mobile app, and app store. It requires repeatedly typing a long master passphrase.\nPeople do not like to hear it but password managers are BAD. Even the best of them is so bad that I struggle to use it. (I do because I have no alternative.)\nhttps://idlewords.com/2019/05/what_i_learned_trying_to_secure_congressional_campaigns.htm ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15497/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Agile","RelPermalink":"/categories/agile/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Internet","RelPermalink":"/categories/internet/"}],"content":"Tooling has become so good and so empowering that like in this tweet, many commerce startups that are really struggling to hire and retain dev teams (and then utilize them to their potential) would be much better served using Airtable, Zapier and Pipedrive until they break.\nMore likely in any case that the startup will go out of business or be acquired than it hitting the limits of those kinds of tools.\nhttps://twitter.com/calebhicks/status/1133517102181040128 ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15485/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Deutsch","RelPermalink":"/categories/deutsch/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Reading","RelPermalink":"/categories/reading/"},{"LinkTitle":"Science","RelPermalink":"/categories/science/"}],"content":"I was arguing against Systems Theory today (a necessary evil when you live in Germany) which prompted the thought of searching for the conjunction of Bruno Latour and Niklas Luhmann. That led me to this gem .\nIt turns out that they met each other for a debate in 1996 in Bielefeld and Latour DESTROYED his opponent ( full article ).\nLuhmann, as expected, failed to engage with the theme of the conference, Science and Technology Studies and didn\u0026rsquo;t come out of his bubble. The same bubble that he has managed to trap most of the German humanities in.\n[Luhmann] only managed to address the theme of the conferencescience and its sociological studywith half a sentence where he curtly asserted that science is an autopoietic subsystem of modern society.\nAn autopoietic subsystem, my ass. Latour quickly riposted into a frontal assault at the entirety of Luhmann-ism.\nNo, according to Latour, this theory didn\u0026rsquo;t have anything to offer to him and neither he concluded any of those gathered there. A quick perusal of the conference program should have sufficed to ascertain that the empirically obsessed STSers could not recover their objects in this theory. This may be bemoaned from the high vantage point of the Theory of Society as poor, theoretically \u0026ldquo;flat\u0026rdquo; sociology, nonetheless, Latour replied, this empirical Zoology of STS gives an account of this society as it is and not how it may appear from the distance of the chilling heights of systems theory.\nLatour clarified that fundamentally, systems theory represents everything that he and his colleagues in science studies have been battling for 20 yearsyes, really battle and not just criticize. The purification of science, the simplification of the social by a demarcation with its environment, Luhmann\u0026rsquo;s work as the embodiment of the \u0026ldquo;cognitive turn\u0026rdquo; in epistemologyfor Latour these were the old buzzwords that had to miss what\u0026rsquo;s special about science: its materiality. And in doing so of course also what\u0026rsquo;s specific for modern society, the large technological networks.\nLatour battling the purification of science [and] the simplification of the social, a true hero of science and society.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/the-theory-of-society/","tags":[],"title":"The Theory of Society"},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Berlin","RelPermalink":"/categories/berlin/"},{"LinkTitle":"Deutsch","RelPermalink":"/categories/deutsch/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"}],"content":"From a thread about whether it is possible or not to live in Berlin without a car (gasp!). This is what a normal odd day of mine looks like.\nThe car isn\u0026rsquo;t the problem or more like: having a car would be a problem. During those rush hours, doing the same journeys by car would take at least twice as long.\n07:00 aufstehen, Kinder anziehen, KiTa brot machen 07:45 Lastenrad holen, noch was anziehen usw., Kinder berzeugen einzusteigen 08:10 Abfahrt zum Kita (andere Seite von Kreuzberg, 2.8km) 08:25 Kita Ankunft 08:40 Idealfall Abfahrt Kita zur Arbeit (Schneberg, 7.7km) 09:10 Sitze auf dem Arbeitsplatz 16:30 Abfahrt Arbeit (weil ich sie gebracht habe muss ich sie jetzt nicht abholen, kann auch 16:00 sein oder 17:00) 16:45 Biomarkt wenn wir noch einkaufen brauchen 17:10 Abfahrt Biomarkt 17:25 sptestens wieder zu Hause Den nchsten Tag tue ich das gleiche andersrum mit dem Zwilingsrad und hole die um 15:30 ab beim Kita. Ich fahre ungefhr 15km Rad pro Tag.\nIch arbeite 30 Stunden aber das ist nicht wegen des Autos oder so sondern weil ich meine Kinder auch ab und zu noch sehen mchte.\nMit Auto wren wir nicht schneller (eher viel langsamer weil Stau + Parkplatzsuche usw.) also das macht fr unsere Stunden gar keinen Unterschied.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/living-without-a-car-in-berlin/","tags":[],"title":"Living without a car in Berlin"},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Nederlands","RelPermalink":"/categories/nederlands/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"}],"content":"Leave it to the Netherlands to have a Green party that is right-wing just like every other party. Their leader, Jesse Klaver, styled himself after Trudeau during his campaign but after that, the result has been a bit lackluster without a seat in government.\nBelow is the story how they backstabbed our boyor more wayward sonZihni zdil because he didn\u0026rsquo;t kowtow to the great leader.\nhttps://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2019/05/30/opkomst-en-ondergang-van-een-bevlogen-kamerlid-a3962131 ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15477/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Nederlands","RelPermalink":"/categories/nederlands/"},{"LinkTitle":"Science","RelPermalink":"/categories/science/"}],"content":"Fijn zo\u0026rsquo;n land onder de zeespiegel dat wordt beheerst door klimaatontkenners. En gezien het Nederlandse asielbeleid is het niet heel waarschijnlijk dat klimaatvluchtelingen elders op een warm welkom zullen kunnen rekenen.\nhttps://twitter.com/Jamrat _/status/1132546604366475264\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15475/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"},{"LinkTitle":"Work","RelPermalink":"/categories/work/"}],"content":"Gitlab\u0026rsquo;s CEO Shadow Program is a testament to their deep and deliberate thinking about organizational development. I\u0026rsquo;m curious whether more companies do this.\nhttps://about.gitlab.com/handbook/ceo/shadow/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15470/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Art","RelPermalink":"/categories/art/"},{"LinkTitle":"Berlin","RelPermalink":"/categories/berlin/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"}],"content":"I had no idea but it seems Berlin has a booming Chinese art scene.\nhttps://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2019/05/why-chinas-expat-artists-move-berlin/589951/?utm_source=twitter\u0026amp;utm_medium=social\u0026amp;utm_campaign=share ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15468/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Barcelona","RelPermalink":"/categories/barcelona/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Travel","RelPermalink":"/categories/travel/"}],"content":"Cities like Barcelona are starting to fight back against AirBnB and tourism.\nhttps://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/04/29/the-airbnb-invasion-of-barcelona I recently refused to help some local tourists to call the bike share hotline in German. We were legitimately in a hurry but my flat out refusal was not appreciated. Next time I\u0026rsquo;ll tell them I won\u0026rsquo;t be helping them because I do not support tourism.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15466/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Nederlands","RelPermalink":"/categories/nederlands/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"},{"LinkTitle":"Reading","RelPermalink":"/categories/reading/"}],"content":"Ik dacht dat Arjen van Veelen n van de beste schrijvers op de Correspondent was. Dat is hij misschien nog steeds, maar dan shrijft hij wel dit soort onzin.\nhttps://twitter.com/GijsbertPols/status/1133034973437599744 ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15464/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Deutsch","RelPermalink":"/categories/deutsch/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Internet","RelPermalink":"/categories/internet/"}],"content":"Set aside all of the obvious outcry, I haven\u0026rsquo;t seen a single argument yet that explains how encrypted communications are compatible with state power.\nhttps://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/horst-seehofer-will-messengerdienste-zum-entschluesseln-zwingen-a-1269121.html I listened to this and didn\u0026rsquo;t hear that explanation nor did I find many of the arguments against very convincing.\nhttps://logbuch-netzpolitik.de/lnp302-wir-wollen-euch-nur-ein-bisschen-abkuehlen ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15460/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Internet","RelPermalink":"/categories/internet/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"}],"content":"Swisher is doing good work here on Facebook/Fakebook but her handling of the worst of technology is still astonishingly softball given what is happening.\nhttps://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/26/opinion/nancy-pelosi-facebook-video.html ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15458/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Work","RelPermalink":"/categories/work/"}],"content":"A huge deep dive into how Stripe invests in technical infrastructure that contains too many good things to list.\nPrioritize as much work into the future as possible, shedding \u0026ldquo;forced\u0026rdquo; work.\nTo start digging out, sometimes you can get creative, finding more leveraged approach, push on the constraints a few times to make sure you\u0026rsquo;re not being rigid. The goal here is to find work that addresses \u0026ldquo;forced\u0026rdquo; work that also reduces future \u0026ldquo;forced\u0026rdquo; work.\nConsider getting product managers into your infrastructure organization. Not every team needs them all the time, but having even a few who can help navigate the transition from firefighting to innovating is super helpful.\nIf your team is doing forced, short-term work, then dig out by investing into your operational excellence.\nIf your team is just starting to experience the thrills of discretionary, long-term work, then invest into your product management skills.\nIf you have discretionary budget, but still find yourself running from one problem, then identify the principles to balance your approach, and set baselines for each principle.\nhttps://lethain.com/how-to-invest-technical-infrastructure/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15456/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Kids","RelPermalink":"/categories/kids/"},{"LinkTitle":"Work","RelPermalink":"/categories/work/"}],"content":"I am hard out at three 2/3 days a week to pick up my children and stayed at home last Friday to take care of a sick kid, so I am doing my best to parent very much out in the open in my workplace. It helps that my grandboss is also very explicit about this but I still find it difficult.\nhttps://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/05/normalize-parenthood-workplace-dont-hide-it/589822/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15454/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Product-/-Design","RelPermalink":"/categories/product-/-design/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":" code is just a high precision design medium\nhttps://twitter.com/PavelASamsonov/status/1127207381673418752 From an interesting discussion of the nuances between product and design strategy a notable tidbit that sheds a lot of light.\nAlso while we are discussing the ever-shifting definition of design, here\u0026rsquo;s another interesting tweet.\nhttps://twitter.com/MargoDunlap/status/1094073270910046209 You see this a lot with design wanting a seat at the table but more often than not at those tables (which are inexplicably always at the highest echelons of power either in companies or government), most designers will not have the first clue what to contribute.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15450/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"}],"content":"The play: SPD goes populist-nationalist to catch all of the right-wing worker votes and nibble off from AfD/CDU. They leave the open society social-democratic policies to the Greens.\nI\u0026rsquo;m not sure whether in that constellation Green and SPD would be able to work together anymore. In Denmark the labour party has taken a hard right like that and it\u0026rsquo;s a bit difficult to stomach. Still, I\u0026rsquo;d prefer those votes to go to classical labour parties instead of going to fascists.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15447/","tags":[],"title":"The future of social democracy"},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Kids","RelPermalink":"/categories/kids/"},{"LinkTitle":"Music","RelPermalink":"/categories/music/"}],"content":"After their long nap, I took both out for a round of recycling cardboard, pumping some tires and buying some coffee beans ((Johann \u0026amp; Nystrm at Chapter One)).\nBoth of them put on their helmets of their own accord and jumped into the Christiania as soon as we got there. It was clear that they had a destination in mind. They then tried to describe to me which playground they wanted to go to and how to get there lacking most of the vocabulary to do so. Extremely adorable and no doubt in my mind that they\u0026rsquo;ll be able to describe their wishes here pretty soon as well.\nOn the way back both kids were singing something in the cargobike while I in the back was trying to vocalize a rendition of Lemon Tree from very distant memory. We should definitely install a sound system in the bike.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/to-christiania/","tags":[],"title":"To Christiania!"},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Reading","RelPermalink":"/categories/reading/"}],"content":" In her estimation, I knew, I was assured a safe life, an easy life, a fine education, every opportunity. I would never have to eat rationed food, or obey curfews, or watch riots from my rooftop, or hide neighbors in water tanks to prevent them from being shot, as she and my father had.\nIn my son\u0026rsquo;s eyes I see the ambition that had first hurled me across the world. In a few years he will graduate and pave his way, alone and unprotected. But I remind myself that he has a father who is still living, a mother who is happy and strong. Whenever he is discouraged I tell him that if I can survive on three continents than there is no obstacle he cannot conquer.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/highlights-for-interpreter-of-maladies/","tags":[],"title":"Highlights for Interpreter of Maladies"},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Reading","RelPermalink":"/categories/reading/"}],"content":" What risks are acceptable is often not documented, and when they are, they are stated in soft, unquantified terms that cannot be used clearly in a calculation to determine if a given expenditure is justified or not.\nMeasurement: A quantitatively expressed reduction of uncertainty based on one or more observations.\nIf a decision maker or analyst engages in what they believe to be measurement activities, but their estimates and decisions actually get worse or dont at least improve, then they are not actually reducing their error and are not conducting a measurement according to the stated definition.\nWhat you want to know is whether you have less uncertainty after considering some source of data and whether that reduction in uncertainty warrants some change in actions.\nWe can measure the value of art, free time, or reducing risk to your life by assessing how much people actually pay for these things.\nIf your concern is that upper management wont understand this, we can say we have not observed thiseven when weve been told that management wouldnt understand it. In fact, upper management seems to understand having to determine which risks are acceptable at least as well as anyone in cybersecurity.\nSince we know at least one (if not both) must be wrong, then we know qualifications and expertise in cybersecurity alone are not sufficient to determine if a given opinion on this topic is correct.\nMore fundamentally, does it even matter whether risk analysis works? And by works,do we really just mean whether it succeeds in putting on a show for compliance, or should we mean it actually improves the identification and management of risks?\nThey are all based in part on the idea that not knowing exact quantities is the same as knowing nothing of any value.\nAll of the operations just described require some source of an input. In this example, we will be using the calibrated estimates of the CISO. Since the CISO is using his previous experience and his calibrated probability-assessment skill to generate the inputs, we call them an informative prior.\nPractically speaking, there are only so many models that can be run and maintained at any given time.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/highlights-for-how-to-measure-anything-in-cybersecurity-risk/","tags":[],"title":"Highlights for How to Measure Anything in Cybersecurity Risk"},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Berlin","RelPermalink":"/categories/berlin/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"}],"content":"Berlin will also regularly call on McKinsey to fix its problems. As this description of them giving Puerto Rico the Greece-treatment shows, where they come nothing good will follow.\nhttp://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/04/mckinsey-in-puerto-rico.html ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15437/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Agile","RelPermalink":"/categories/agile/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"}],"content":"With my background in behavior change, I\u0026rsquo;m very pleasantly surprised to find this quote in what is a connoisseur\u0026rsquo;s treatment of the nuances of agile/agility: There is only one way to create business value, and thats to change someones behavior.\nhttps://medium.com/columbus-egg/iterating-pivoting-agile-agility-940bcb1a0895 ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15435/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Work","RelPermalink":"/categories/work/"}],"content":" Admittedly, this neat combination of worshipping totems while pursuing practical benefits is quintessentially Chinese.\nA critical but hopeful treatment of Chinese and wider tech culture as seen through the radical lens of Burning Man.\nhttps://logicmag.io/07-the-chinese-burner/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15432/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Reading","RelPermalink":"/categories/reading/"}],"content":"A lot of very salient thinking on books, metacognition, double-loop learning and the deliberate design of new forms by Andy Matuschak in Why Books Don\u0026rsquo;t Work .\nI acknowledged earlier that of course, some people do absorb knowledge from books. Indeed, those are the people who really do think about what theyre reading. The process is often invisible. These readers inner monologues have sounds like: This idea reminds me of,This point conflicts with,I dont really understand how,etc. If they take some notes, theyre not simply transcribing the authors words: theyre summarizing, synthesizing, analyzing.\nI\u0026rsquo;ve been thinking of doing a talk about how to get the most out of your reading both quantitatively and qualitatively. Many people do not even know how much is possible, let alone that they would have an inkling of how to get there. I think anybody can easily get to at least a doubling of reading quantity and conceptual retention.\nReaders must decide which exercises to do and when. Readers must run their own feedback loops: did they clearly understand the ideas involved in the exercise? If not, what should they do next? What should students do if theyre completely stuck? Some issues are subtler. For example, textbook exercises are often designed to yield both a solution to that specific problem and also broader insights about the subject. Will readers notice if they solved a problem but missed the insights it was supposed to reveal?\nWork in new aesthetic and educational forms along with opening up systems to allow people to make their own rules for going through them, is all of the stuff we had been occupied with in Hubbub as well.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15431/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Nederlands","RelPermalink":"/categories/nederlands/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"}],"content":"Of de Nederlandse omroepen en kranten nou extreem-rechts zijn of niet, het effect is hetzelfde. Ze ondersteunen systematisch politiek en politici die rechts of heel rechts zijn.\nhttps://www.human.nl/medialogica/lees/Hoe-een-ultrarechts-campagnespotje-op-de-publieke-omroep-kon-worden-uitgezonden.html ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15429/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Deutsch","RelPermalink":"/categories/deutsch/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"},{"LinkTitle":"Video","RelPermalink":"/categories/video/"}],"content":"A collective of the largest German YouTubers have just before the European elections launched a campaign against the CDU and it\u0026rsquo;s a joy to see.\nThe CDU which is usually fully ignorant when it comes to digital issues has taken this broadside seriously. That by itself was a huge mistake. Most serious institutions would and should brush off something coming from new media.\nWhether this will have an effect is hugely unclear. The core CDU audience is disconnected and apathetic but they do get a lot of votes from other segments as well and there they could be slightly vulnerable. In any case, the series of fumbles that the CDU has embarked upon while trying to address this has only served to give the boycott movement wings.\nWhat\u0026rsquo;s interesting about the YouTubers is that they break with the German institutional consensus which is white, male and old. That group of people has a certain set of opinions and interests which has made sure that Germany has become increasingly backward. The YouTubers are young, (judging by their names and handles) diverse and not all male. And most importantly they have reach and fewer entrenched interests.\nhttps://www.tagesspiegel.de/politik/neues-video-von-rezo-mehr-als-70-youtube-stars-rufen-zum-boykott-von-cdu-und-spd-auf/24379566.html?fbclid=IwAR2jbOBkIBldbxKy6HN45qqt9N8CotfCYP-4h1mBosolneeTcknxFxgTjCY ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/youtube-hatchet-job-on-the-cdu/","tags":[],"title":"YouTube hatchet job on the CDU"},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Product-/-Design","RelPermalink":"/categories/product-/-design/"}],"content":" The key to building this aura is to become increasingly detail oriented, to be more prepared than anyone else, and to have a higher bar than those around you.\nI\u0026rsquo;ve always dabbled heavily in product but reading something like this really gets me hyped up to consider switching into Product Management.\nhttps://hackernoon.com/how-to-get-into-product-management-78c58bd9c8cf?sk=4acbf6fd7e8d2d9887bde3605ad2584f ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15421/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"The issue around the Python standard library finally comes to a head thanks to a Twisted contributor. The standard library has felt stale for a very long time now. It\u0026rsquo;s nice that it\u0026rsquo;s there but nobody can really program anything in Python without external packages. There really is no debate here and core Python should support actual programmers.\nhttps://pyfound.blogspot.com/2019/05/amber-brown-batteries-included-but.html ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15419/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Agile","RelPermalink":"/categories/agile/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Internet","RelPermalink":"/categories/internet/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"},{"LinkTitle":"Work","RelPermalink":"/categories/work/"}],"content":" Changes to one teams service may be implemented by another team who needs the enhanced capability by what is called an Away Team. This team works on the Home Teams code to add what it needs according to established engineering standards and then leaves that code in good order to be maintained by the Home Team who owns the service, with help when needed.\nFully embedding your team in another team\u0026rsquo;s context to get something done, seems to me a very interesting compromise between autonomy and collaboration. Every team is an island, but it is ok to travel to another island and if that\u0026rsquo;s not possible, you can still build your own.\nAlso more than disorienting to see an in-depth piece about engineering organizations like this appear on The Register.\nPutting an entire team in another team\u0026rsquo;s context is something I have considered for all the collaboration, delivery, culture etc. benefits that it will most likely yield in exchange for a minor hit in delivery.\nhttps://www.theregister.co.uk/2019/05/14/amazons_away_teams/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15417/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"}],"content":"Venkat\u0026rsquo;s newsletter Life Spirit Distillationhas a nice argument against personal growth and instead in favor of life intensification reframing the question into:\nW hat do you do with the unexpected person you find you\u0026rsquo;ve turned into?\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/personal-growth/","tags":[],"title":"Personal Growth"},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"}],"content":"https://twitter.com/TheOnion/status/1128726771942219781 Germany has a lot to improve as well when it comes to pro choice, but it is nowhere near as dire as the USA. If you have money to give, The Yellowhammer Fund seems to be a good place to donate to.\nhttps://yellowhammerfund.org/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15415/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Internet","RelPermalink":"/categories/internet/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"},{"LinkTitle":"Work","RelPermalink":"/categories/work/"}],"content":"Many years ago I suggested building in async facilities into Django. I got ridiculed for that both for technical feasibility (rightly) and necessity (short-sightedly). Now finally we have a proposal to build those features into the framework that demonstrates the same need and that can be implemented.\nhttps://github.com/andrewgodwin/deps/blob/async/draft/0009-async.rst ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15410/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Science","RelPermalink":"/categories/science/"},{"LinkTitle":"Work","RelPermalink":"/categories/work/"}],"content":"This article about forecasting dovetails nicely with the book about measuring risk that I just read. It makes the case for foxlike thinking, something of which I don\u0026rsquo;t need to be persuaded.\nAmong those, they identified a small group of the foxiest forecastersbright people with extremely wide-ranging interests and unusually expansive reading habits, but no particular relevant backgroundand weighted team forecasts toward their predictions. They destroyed the competition.\nTetlock and Mellers found that not only were the best forecasters foxy as individuals, but they tended to have qualities that made them particularly effective collaborators. They were curious about, well, really everything,as one of the top forecasters told me. They crossed disciplines, and viewed their teammates as sources for learning, rather than peers to be convinced. When those foxes were later grouped into much smaller teams12 members eachthey became even more accurate. They outperformedby a lota group of experienced intelligence analysts with access to classified data.\nhttps://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2019/06/how-to-predict-the-future/588040/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15408/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"},{"LinkTitle":"Product-/-Design","RelPermalink":"/categories/product-/-design/"}],"content":"It\u0026rsquo;s exciting to see the Emirates government put design front and center. Unfortunately though in a closed context such as that, it is more than likely that design will be instrumentalized and deployed only for material gain.\nhttps://design.gov.ae/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15406/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Work","RelPermalink":"/categories/work/"}],"content":"A book and an overview of how career opportunities are closed off to those without the right background and how to be cognizant of this and correct for it.\nhttps://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/02/class-ceiling-laurison-friedman-elite-jobs/582175/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15404/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Deutsch","RelPermalink":"/categories/deutsch/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Internet","RelPermalink":"/categories/internet/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"},{"LinkTitle":"Work","RelPermalink":"/categories/work/"}],"content":"Usually it\u0026rsquo;s not for a good reason but still, it\u0026rsquo;s nice to see my grand-boss Dror on television regularly explaining cybersecurity to the German public.\nhttps://www.daserste.de/information/wirtschaft-boerse/plusminus/videos/daten-gefahr-unternehmen-video-100.html ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15402/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"}],"content":"Not a word wrong in this piece, landlords are the original rent-seeking leeches.\nhttps://www.huckmag.com/perspectives/opinion-perspectives/there-is-no-such-thing-as-a-good-landlord/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15398/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"},{"LinkTitle":"The-City","RelPermalink":"/categories/the-city/"}],"content":"Innisfil, Ontario\u0026rsquo;s troubles filling in their public transit with Uber is a great example of how governments should not outsource things to private contractors whose unit economics do not make sense.\nhttps://www.citylab.com/transportation/2019/04/innisfil-transit-ride-hailing-bus-public-transportation-uber/588154/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15395/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Games","RelPermalink":"/categories/games/"},{"LinkTitle":"Internet","RelPermalink":"/categories/internet/"},{"LinkTitle":"Kids","RelPermalink":"/categories/kids/"},{"LinkTitle":"Nederlands","RelPermalink":"/categories/nederlands/"}],"content":"Deze Nederlandstalige app van Juf Jannie belooft puzzels voor kinderen vanaf 2 jaar aan te bieden maar de interactie en gebruiksvriendelijkheid zijn erbarmelijk slecht.\nIk heb mijn geld terug gevraagd en ik raad aan andere mensen dat ook te doen bij apps die onder de maat zijn.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/puzzels-kinderen-van-juf-jannie/","tags":[],"title":"Puzzels kinderen van Juf Jannie"},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Internet","RelPermalink":"/categories/internet/"},{"LinkTitle":"Video","RelPermalink":"/categories/video/"},{"LinkTitle":"Work","RelPermalink":"/categories/work/"}],"content":"Even given that this is an amazing job description, you don\u0026rsquo;t often see companies describing themselves as a socio-technical system. This is a great way to show off both your care and your depth of thinking.\nhttps://jobs.netflix.com/jobs/869465 ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15392/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Work","RelPermalink":"/categories/work/"}],"content":"Fascinating to read about the care with which Slack designs their workplaces.\nhttps://www.fastcompany.com/90341688/slacks-head-of-workplace-design-thinks-open-floor-plans-suuuck ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15390/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Berlin","RelPermalink":"/categories/berlin/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"}],"content":"A paean for canteens something of which Berlin has ample for a variety of historic reasons.\nhttps://dinnerdocument.com/2019/04/30/i-dream-of-canteens/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15388/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Product-/-Design","RelPermalink":"/categories/product-/-design/"}],"content":"I can confirm most of the best practices from this guide of Stack Overflow\u0026rsquo;s remote first design culture.\nhttp://www.tedgoas.com/blog/distributed-design ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15385/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"New-York","RelPermalink":"/categories/new-york/"},{"LinkTitle":"Reading","RelPermalink":"/categories/reading/"}],"content":"https://www.niemanlab.org/2019/05/what-will-the-correspondent-publish-in-english-a-look-at-the-dutch-site-offers-some-clues/ Americans feel ripped off by the Corres\u0026rsquo;s bait and switch and it seems now we\u0026rsquo;re going to seeing a free for all where they will mercilessly rip the site.\nIt was disappointing to realize  to actually see in the numbers  that while The Correspondent raised $2.6 million in part by stressing diversity and inclusivity, tapping ambassadors like DeRay Mckesson and Baratunde Thurston, the Dutch site is not a model of that diversity.\nThere is a lot of criticism and hate in the Netherlands as well but it\u0026rsquo;s not so pronounced because:\nThe site has its provenance in the Netherlands. It\u0026rsquo;s a small country and you never know who you\u0026rsquo;ll need again in the future (the media in The Netherlands is more tight-knit, insular, and male than it is in the U.S.). The USA is not bothered by either of those and that creates a more honest environment because frankly a lot of the criticism is valid.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15382/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Product-/-Design","RelPermalink":"/categories/product-/-design/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"}],"content":"A Mac app that turns any website into a handy application, another wild app exploration by Morten Just.\nhttps://flotato.lpages.co/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15380/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Games","RelPermalink":"/categories/games/"},{"LinkTitle":"Kids","RelPermalink":"/categories/kids/"},{"LinkTitle":"Nederlands","RelPermalink":"/categories/nederlands/"}],"content":"Zhlen fr die Kleinsten 123 heb ik gekocht omdat er een Nederlandse versie van is (inclusief de audio). Helaas is de kwaliteit te slecht om dat vaker aan te horen en de interactiviteit laat veel te wensen over.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/toddler-counting-123/","tags":[],"title":"Toddler Counting 123"},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Games","RelPermalink":"/categories/games/"},{"LinkTitle":"Kids","RelPermalink":"/categories/kids/"},{"LinkTitle":"Nederlands","RelPermalink":"/categories/nederlands/"}],"content":"Dikkie Dik spelletjes is een officiele app van de uitgever Gottmer. Het is een rijke verzameling spelletjes maar over het algemeen matig bruikbaar en ongeschikt voor kinderen van 2 jaar oud.\n","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/dikkie-dik-spelletjes/","tags":[],"title":"Dikkie Dik spelletjes"},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Politics","RelPermalink":"/categories/politics/"},{"LinkTitle":"The-City","RelPermalink":"/categories/the-city/"},{"LinkTitle":"Travel","RelPermalink":"/categories/travel/"}],"content":"The economic costs Airbnb imposes likely outweigh the benefits.\nI don\u0026rsquo;t think anybody will be surprised by this study whose conclusions are that AirBnB is a drain on society and should be taxed and regulated mercilessly.\nhttps://www.epi.org/publication/the-economic-costs-and-benefits-of-airbnb-no-reason-for-local-policymakers-to-let-airbnb-bypass-tax-or-regulatory-obligations/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15363/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Work","RelPermalink":"/categories/work/"}],"content":"Something that sounds so basic and is so very important but that can be very difficult to achieve when you\u0026rsquo;re in the thick of it: Work on the business, not in the business.\nhttps://knowyourteam.com/blog/2019/04/24/work-on-the-business-and-not-in-the-business-as-leaders/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15361/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Reading","RelPermalink":"/categories/reading/"},{"LinkTitle":"Science","RelPermalink":"/categories/science/"}],"content":" As youll see, everything is slightly approximate, slightly exaggerated  so that each step in the argument takes you further from what youre prepared to agree to.\nIt turns out Harari\u0026rsquo;s books only go downhill after Sapiens.\nhttp://www.thewhitereview.org/reviews/yuval-noah-harari/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15358/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Agile","RelPermalink":"/categories/agile/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Product-/-Design","RelPermalink":"/categories/product-/-design/"}],"content":"A worth-while apology for Design Thinking:\nThis is why I advise executives study design. If culture is driven by leadership behavior, then culture change is primarily driven by leadership behavior change. Design has a lot of techniques to offer.\nhttps://medium.com/columbus-egg/design-thinking-as-decision-framing-7d6795542421 ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15356/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"Agile","RelPermalink":"/categories/agile/"},{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Internet","RelPermalink":"/categories/internet/"},{"LinkTitle":"Software-Engineering","RelPermalink":"/categories/software-engineering/"},{"LinkTitle":"Work","RelPermalink":"/categories/work/"}],"content":"The newsworthy thing about the Accenture/Hertz story is not that they failed to deliver but how badly they failed and that they are getting sued for it. Getting something that\u0026rsquo;s not very good for far too much money is an accepted part of doing business with consultancies of that size.\nhttps://www.theregister.co.uk/2019/04/23/hertz_accenture_lawsuit/ ","permalink":"http://localhost:1313/blog/15354/","tags":[],"title":""},{"categories":[{"LinkTitle":"English","RelPermalink":"/categories/english/"},{"LinkTitle":"Internet","RelPermalink":"/categories/internet/"},{"LinkTitle":"Video","RelPermalink":"/categories/video/"}],"content":" Everyone else, money manager big or small, met with him virtually, over Zoom. When Yuan flew to New York for the IPO, it was just his eighth work trip in five years.\nZoom is the real deal and the story behind its success is immensely inspiring.\nhttps://www.forbes.com/sites/alexkonrad/2019/04/19/zoom-zoom